<HEAD>Former Prime Minister Returns To Government Post</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to ADD Shiite background of Kishtmand and
UPDATE with rebels trying to break deadlock on forming interim govt. Pick
up 8th pvs, `The guerrillas'...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHARON HERBAUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Sultan </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Kishtmand </PERSON>, a ranking member of the ruling <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s Politburo and a hard-liner, Tuesday took over many of the duties of prime minister, government sources said. Moslem guerrillas, meanwhile, fired a salvo of rockets into the Afghan capital, killing one person and injuring three others on the ninth anniversary of an uprising against the Soviet-backed government. <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Hasan </PERSON> <PERSON> Sharq </PERSON> stepped down as prime minister Monday, and a 21-member <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Military </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> took power. State-run <ORGANIZATION> Kabul </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON> Kishtmand </PERSON>, who served as prime minister for seven years until May 1988, is in charge of supervising the government's council of ministers. Government sources, speaking on condition of anonyumity, said this means the 52-year-old Kishtmand will effectively be the prime minister. The return to power of of <LOCATION> Kishtmand </LOCATION>, the only prominent Shiite Moslem in President <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>'s government, is seen as another move by <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> to consolidate the power of his communist government. Shiites make up only 17 percent of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s population, but they account for about 40 percent of the refugees from which many of the guerrillas are drawn. <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> appointed <ORGANIZATION> Sharq </ORGANIZATION>, a non-communist, as prime minister last May in an unsucessful bid to seek a power-sharing agreement with the Moslem guerrillas. In <LOCATION> Islamabad </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, a committee of Afghan field commanders and scholars sought to reach a consensus Tuesday on the makeup of an interim government for <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. More than 400 delegates to a special Afghan council or `` shura'' canceled Tuesday's session while the committee wrestled with a blueprint for a provisional government. The commanders and scholars took over the job of nominating an interim government after guerrilla leaders, paralyzed by differences between moderates and fundamentalists, failed to break a deadlock Monday. The guerrillas' rocket attack on <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> was the first since Thursday, when at least seven people were killed. The <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said the fatal rocket in Tuesday's assault hit near a government refugee office in northern <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>. Three other rockets hit southeastern <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, but there were no reports of casualties. The guerrillas hold most of the countryside and are trying to close in on the cities, which mainly are held by government troops. At the headquarters of the secret police, the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> displayed a huge cache of arms and explosives and said the guerrillas had planned to use them Tuesday to attack buildings and bazaars. Many had markings from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>. Officials said others were made in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, where the most powerful guerrilla groups are based. <PERSON> Moammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Omar </PERSON>, a state security agent, said the weapons were seized Monday in a well in eastern <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>. Business was brisk at some shops in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> Tuesday, but others were closed to mark the anniversary of the anti-Soviet uprising. The 1980 revolt occurred two months after Soviet troops entered <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> to bolster a Marxist government. Soviet soldiers fired on Moslem protesters who emerged from their homes shouting `` God is Great!'' Dozens of people were reported killed. Among the weapons displayed by the government were plastic explosives that agents said came from <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, Chinese-made hand grenades, British mortar shells, Egyptian rockets, Italian fuses for mines, Swedish circuit testers and <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> rifles. There also were political pamphlets. One, printed in English and the local language <LOCATION> Dari </LOCATION>, said: `` We will contine our Jihad -LRB- holy war -RRB- until the withdrawal of the last Soviet soldier.'' The final Soviet troops, once estimated at more than 100,000 in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, withdrew last Wednesday under a U.N.-mediated accord. Over the weekend, <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> declared a state of emergency and shook up his government to consolidate control. In <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> Tuesday, an investigator appointed by the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> said both sides in the civil war continue to violate the human rights of Afghans. Austrian law professor <PERSON> Felix </PERSON> <PERSON> Ermacora </PERSON> said reliable reports suggest dfghan police still widely use torture and mistreatment as part of interrogations. His report also listed alleged incidents, cited by `` a variety of corroborating sources,'' in which rebels had killed more than 100 Afghan soldiers and civilians since September.
