<SECOND>PM-Bad Times on Bayou II,1246</SECOND>
<HEAD>Part II: Economic Reform Comes Hard In Populist Louisiana</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 When the oil and the good times were flowing, <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>'s populist system of government seemed to make sense. Give the people a free ride and let the businesses pay. Now oil has crashed, <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> has suffered through four years of economic depression, and economists say recovery is n't possible without a new system. A reformist governor is trying to do just that, but breaking with the populist past does n't come easy. This second of two parts of `` Bad Times On The Bayou'' explores this <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> revolution.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By SCOTT McCARTNEY</NOTE>
<NOTE>Associated Press Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The 34-story <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> state capitol casts a long shadow over the white marble statue of <PERSON> Huey </PERSON> <PERSON> Long </PERSON>, but these days, it seems the statue is casting the longer shadow. `` An unconquered friend of the poor,'' the inscription on Long's adjacent tomb says, `` who dreamed of the day when the wealth of the land would be spread among the people. The populist ideas of `` the Kingfish,'' who governed from 1928-1932, still influence the fiscal structure of the state. Spread the wealth, protect the poor. Homeowners receive a $ 75,000 property tax exemption, making the average home tax free. Automobile license plates cost only $ 3 a year. City councils ca n't raise taxes without a vote of the people. Businesses bear much of the burden through taxes and fees. But the way of doing business that <PERSON> Huey </PERSON> <PERSON> Long </PERSON> helped build is crippling the state now, economists say. Without the oil windfall, state and local budgets ca n't be balanced. Schools and hospitals are suffering. Unemployment has soared. And new businesses are scared away by the tax structure. `` It's ironic. What is supposed to be good for the people now acts to their detriment,'' said <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orleans </ORGANIZATION> economist <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON>. Added business leader <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Schreiber </PERSON>, director of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>' World Trade Center: `` We've got to change We can not do business in the old ways. ... Painful as it is, it's forced us to wake up.'' But waking up is n't easy in the land of `` The Big Easy,'' as <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> is called. After a string of legislative victories and a fierce round of budget cutting and borrowing, Gov. <PERSON> Buddy </PERSON> <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON>'s initial attempt at overhauling the tax structure failed in the state House. The Harvard-educated conservative Democrat has, in his own words, `` poked every bear in the forest'' while inciting a revolution in <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>. He won education reform, campaign finance reform, tort reform, worker's compensation reform, even unemployment insurance reform. But when it came to fiscal reform, when it came to dismantling the last vestiges of the populist past, <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> lost. Ca n't a family's home be the one thing that's not taxed, <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON>'s opponents asked `` I believe in paying our own way. That is a break from <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> tradition,'' <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> said. `` It does n't come easy.'' Along the way, <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> is also compiling a spectrum of political enemies ranging from populists to labor unions to teachers. Public opinion polls are divided on the maverick reformer. The question remains, what happens if he ca n't complete the revolution? `` It would be more of the same. We'd be a slave to <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> ... a wasteland, a welfare state,'' <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> said, adding that people with the means to move away would do so. Politicians, he said, `` are beginning to realize that.'' Fiscal reform has become the vortex of <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>'s struggle to climb out of a depression that began when the price of oil fell by more than half in 1984-85. Tens of thousands lost jobs, and both businesses and workers left the state. And taxes on oil _ which used to account for 40 percent of the <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> state budget _ plummeted. The state, long known for its big spending ways, had n't put anything aside for dry years. It had n't spent much on developing a strong economic base, outside of oil. In fact, it had n't even had a balanced budget in the 1980s until <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> took office 10 months ago _ even though it has a balanced budget law. It's debt reached $ 2 billion. `` We could not make the payroll the week after I took office,'' <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> said. Now, state promoters, planners and business leaders all buzz with talk about <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>'s recovery _ if there is fiscal reform. `` When the price of oil was $ 40 a barrel, hardly anybody worried,'' said <PERSON> Schreiber </PERSON>, the businessman who chaired a governor's task force on labor `` Having all these advantages made everyone in the state very lazy. <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> has not been competitive in business,'' <PERSON> Schreiber </PERSON> said. `` It's only really now that the state is pulling its act together.'' The day after reform failed last October, two companies considering <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> announced plans to build in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. Other businesses considering a relocation or expansion in the Bayou State are holding off until they see if reform passes, said <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>'s chief of economic development, <PERSON> Connie </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> Wall Street bond brokers set out informal guidelines for what would be necessary to raise the state's bond rating, currently just one notch above junk bonds. Low bond ratings means the state must pay higher interest on its debt. <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> has accomplished all but one item _ fiscal reform, said his chief of staff, <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Cochran </PERSON>. `` They watch us very closely,'' he said. The battle will probably be waged this spring when <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> comes back to the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> with a plan. Last time, his package passed the state <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, but came up 10 votes short of the necessary two-thirds margin in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>. The opposition focused on <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON>'s plan to cut by two-thirds the $ 75,000 homestead exemption _ the nation's highest. It was led by a county tax assessor, <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Chehardy </PERSON>, who saw reform as an attempt to raise taxes and cripple the average homeowner. `` People in <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> read horror stories in other states where property taxes did go wild,'' said <PERSON> Chehardy </PERSON>. `` Government taxes everything. Ca n't there be one thing in life a person can have without being taxed?'' <PERSON> Chehardy </PERSON> says lawmakers should cut the budget, and if there are any tax increases, taxpayers should get a chance to vote. But <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> and his top aides insist the budget has been cut so much _ more than $ 500 million _ that further reductions could cripple the state. Already, they worry about the declining quality of care at state-financed charity hospitals and the ability of cities like <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> to get by without the traditional state support. And the next fiscal year budget has a projected deficit of $ 734 million. The total budget is $ 4.2 billion, but only $ 2.2 billion is discretionary spending _ money that is n't tied to court orders or debt payments. `` Cutting that much -LRB- $ 734 million -RRB- would shut more and more hospitals, cut transportation money and higher education,'' said Commissioner of Administration <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Stine </PERSON>. `` That is, in my mind, shutting down government.'' Still, the early talk of next June's budget is a revolutionary concept by itself in <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, a state that at times balanced its budget for only three-quarters of the year and hoped oil prices would go up.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> McCartney </PERSON> is the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION> regional reporter, based in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>.
