<FIRST>r w PM-NorthTrial-Keker     02-21 0661</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-North Trial-Keker,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lead Prosecutor a Creature of the Courtroom</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-North Trial Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Keker </PERSON>, the lawyer prosecuting <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON> in the Iran-Contra trial, has a reputation for intuitively making the right move in a courtroom. In a civil lawsuit, lawyers for a bank abruptly asked one of <PERSON> Keker </PERSON>'s clients whether he would waive the attorney-client privilege of confidentiality. Reacting to the unorthodox request, <PERSON> Keker </PERSON> quickly said his client _ an investor who alleged he had been defrauded _ would agree to a waiver if the bank was willing to waive the same privilege covering conversations with its attorneys. The bank backed down. Representing an insurance company accused of overcharging its customers, <PERSON> Keker </PERSON> on cross-examination asked an expert witness to select from a stock of well over 100 files the one he considered to be the most egregious example of overcharging. Robert A. <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Nest </PERSON>, a partner in <PERSON> Keker </PERSON>'s <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> law firm, recalls that <PERSON> Keker </PERSON> spent a minute familiarizing himself with the contents of the file selected by the expert and `` then proceeded to tear the witness apart.'' `` Two things about <PERSON> John </PERSON>,'' said <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Nest </PERSON>, his tenacity and his intuition. `` He does n't let a point drop. He will fight all the way to whatever is there. `` He's remarkably intuitively skilled in a courtroom. It's a great athlete's intuition, to know where the ball is and where everything is on the field. <PERSON> John </PERSON> has that kind of intuition. He has an ability to respond to the evidence.'' <PERSON> Keker </PERSON>'s ability `` to kind of sense where the witness is going'' is `` a rare skill in today's lawyer,'' said <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Nest </PERSON>. `` So many of us take deposition after deposition and there's nothing to predict.'' <PERSON> Keker </PERSON>'s weaker points? `` He has as many weaknesses as the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> 49ers,'' said <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Nest </PERSON>. The North case will be <PERSON> Keker </PERSON>'s first as a prosecutor, but his abilities as a defense lawyer translate easily to the other side of the courtroom, says <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> McGivern </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, chief assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney for the northern district of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. `` He's always been aggressive and he can bring that aggression to the prosecution side,'' said <PERSON> McGivern </PERSON>. `` He's aware of the moves of a defense lawyer, having been one himself.'' In short, <PERSON> Keker </PERSON> `` can try a case there's no doubt about that,'' said <PERSON> McGivern </PERSON>, who as a prosecutor has been involved in several cases in which <PERSON> Keker </PERSON> has been a defense attorney. A Vietnam War veteran who served in the Marines and was wounded in combat, <PERSON> Keker </PERSON> is a graduate of <ORGANIZATION> Princeton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> and a founding partner of <ORGANIZATION> Keker </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Brockett </PERSON> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. He has successfully defended movie maker <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON> in a civil lawsuit and won a case in which his client, a <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> society figure and architect, was accused of vehicular manslaughter. After the Iran-Contra affair erupted in 1986, <PERSON> Keker </PERSON> sought work with independent counsel <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>. `` <PERSON> John </PERSON> felt there was an important lesson here for Americans who care about the democratic process and he was intent in participating in the investigation for that reason,'' said <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Nest </PERSON>. <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Nest </PERSON> said <PERSON> Keker </PERSON> had concerns that those involved appeared to have been `` hiding the ball, running foreign policy without the consent of representatives of the people.'' `` The political and legal implications struck me as enormous,'' <PERSON> Keker </PERSON> said of the Iran-Contra episode in an interview last year with The Los Angeles Times. <PERSON> Keker </PERSON>, 45, has more than 15 years as a trial lawyer and relishes the role. `` When you go to court,'' he told the Times, `` you get a chance to be a hero, which is a thing that most people repress the desire for. You also get a chance to fail enormously. `` That sort of edge is something that people who are trial lawyers usually like. You get a chance to do the right thing. You get a chance to do it in a stylish way.''
</TEXT>
