<HEAD>Bush Wants Seoul To Lower Trade Barriers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will use his upcoming trip to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> to reaffirm the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> commitment to that country's security while seeking improved access for American products in South Korean markets, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials say On the final leg of a trip that also will take him to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> plans to spend 4 -LCB- hours in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> capital. There, he will meet with President <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> Tae-woo and other officials and visit some of the more than 40,000 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops stationed in the country. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> departs Wednesday for <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where he will attend Friday's funeral of Japanese Emperor <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> He will spend two nights in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> before flying to <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> on Monday. Although <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials are delighted with the political and economic development of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> in recent years, there is growing impatience over South Korean barriers to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> exports, including beef and fruit. The result is a lopsided trade imbalance in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s favor _ about $ 10 billion last year on total two-way trade of slightly more than $ 30 billion. `` <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> has free access to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> markets. <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> should now open up,'' said one <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official, who spoke on condition that he not be identified further. Another irritant in the relationship between the two countries is the large <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military presence in the capital area. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> officials have been engaged in discussions designed to ease the frictions. There is a small but determined radical movement in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, which is driven primarily by anti-Americanism. The radicals have attacked the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cultural center in <LOCATION> Kwangju </LOCATION> several times over the past month. A principal rallying cry recently has been opposition to the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> visit. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> is a far different country today from the one which <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> saw in 1982, his last visit there. The country's unpopular military dictatorship has been replaced by a democratically elected government, and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> now ranks among the world leaders in economic growth rates. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has made a major contribution to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s prosperity, accounting for 34 percent of the country's exports It is quite a change from the situation in the country during the decade after the armistice ended the Korean War in 1953, when the destitution there was such that some <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials recommended suspending all economic assistance, considering the country's future prospects to be beyond hope. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> has been playing an increasingly active role internationally, establishing trade and diplomatic ties in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and hosting the Olympic Games last September. Last fall, <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> began making peace overtures to <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and asked then-President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> to complement <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s steps with gestures of his own. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> responded by liberalizing rules for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> diplomatic contact with <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Koreans </LOCATION>, encouraging cultural exchanges between the two countries and easing restrictions on tourist travel and the export of humanitarian items to <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. A subsequent exchange of notes included a <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> proposal for formal diplomatic discussions, which the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> regarded as unacceptable because it undercut <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s position. Still, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials have been encouraged by an apparent easing of tensions recently on the peninsula, an area long viewed as having the potential for an outbreak of <ORGANIZATION> East-West </ORGANIZATION> hostilities because of the major stake that both superpowers have there.
