<HEAD>Guerrilla Front to Meet Moroccan King for Second Time</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Polisario guerrilla front says it will hold a second round of talks next week with <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> Hassan </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> to discuss extending a truce and a political solution for the disputed <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sahara </LOCATION>. Polisario leader <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Abdelaziz </PERSON>, speaking to a news conference Monday, also dismissed the newly declared five-nation union of north African Arab states as unviable as long as the conflict over <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sahara </LOCATION> is unresolved. `` It is like building houses on a volcano which can erupt at any time,'' <PERSON> Abdelaziz </PERSON> said, speaking through a translator. The leaders of <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mauritania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Tunisia </LOCATION> declared the union on Friday, but did not disclose details on how it will function. One likely result would be a suspension of aid and support by <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION> for the Polisarios' 13-year war to free <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sahara </LOCATION> from Moroccan rule. <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION> annexed most of the former <LOCATION> Spanish </LOCATION> territory in 1976. <PERSON> Abdelaziz </PERSON> said he received word Sunday that <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> Hassan </PERSON> had agreed to meet a <LOCATION> Polisario </LOCATION> delegation next week, but the date and venue was not set. The king first met the Polisarios for two days in early January. The guerrillas later declared a cease-fire for February to improve the climate for the five-nation summit in <LOCATION> Marrakech </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Abdelaziz </PERSON> said. Asked if the truce could be extended, he said he hoped the meeting with <PERSON> Hassan </PERSON> `` will be an occasion to transfer the truce into a political agreement.'' He said the Polisarios would not relinquish the demand for sovereignty over all of <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sahara </LOCATION>, and rejected the idea of autonomy under a Moroccan flag. The options which should be put to the inhabitants in a referendum are `` total independence or integration into <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION>. For us, the only choice is total independence,'' he said. The Polisario delegation was in <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION> as guest of the governing <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. It was to meet Prime Minister <PERSON> Ingvar </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlsson </PERSON>, opposition leaders and Swedish <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> officials.
