<HEAD>Kenyans Lobby Congress To Maintain Aid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Kenyan diplomats are lobbying <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to block a threat by several congressmen to limit aid to <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION> because of alleged human rights abuses. The effort follows some acerbic criticism by the head of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> panel that appropriates money for foreign aid. `` It will be a cold day in you-know-where before this committee earmarks money for <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>,'' said Rep. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Obey </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Wis </LOCATION>., at a recent hearing on human rights in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> `` Earmarking'' is a method <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> uses to guarantee that select countries receive a certain amount of foreign aid, making them immune from administration attempts to shift assistance to other priorities. The bulk of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> foreign aid is earmarked for about 20 countries, leaving the administration little room for maneuvering with the aid. Economic aid for <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION> has been earmarked for the past three years. Skillful efforts by <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION> and its lobbyists last year brought the military component of the assistance under the protection of the earmark too, despite Obey's objections. <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION> got $ 15 million in military aid, which accounts for about 60 percent of all <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military assistance to sub-Saharan <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, and an additional $ 45 million in economic and development funds. <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION> supporters in the administration and on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> cite the access granted by the strategically placed country to <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> ships at <LOCATION> Mombasa </LOCATION> and to <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> planes at its airfields as reason enough for the financial support. But since last fall, when the aid was appropriated for fiscal year 1989, several other congressmen have joined Obey, head of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Appropriations subcommittee on foreign operations, in criticizing what they view as <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>'s deteriorating human rights situation. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Gray </PERSON>, a member of Obey's committee who also serves as chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> caucus in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, issued a statement at the same hearing critical of <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>, which had been a `` shining star in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and a model for its neighbors over many years,'' had been turning in a different direction in recent years, resulting in an erosion of its human rights record. Specific charges against <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION> by human rights groups, as well as the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s annual international human rights report, include the stifling of political opposition by banning political parties and jailing dissidents. Critics also object to recent constitutional amendments that allow President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> arap </PERSON> <PERSON> Moi </PERSON> to dismiss judges and to detain criminal suspects without trial for up to 14 days. But Kenyan Ambassador <PERSON> Denis </PERSON> <PERSON> Afande </PERSON> said critics fail to understand that <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION> is acting strictly within the bounds of its own constitution and laws. `` <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION> is trying very hard to respect the rule of law,'' he said in an interview. `` The criticism here is very demoralizing to my people.'' Other African nations have much worse records than <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>, he said, and many Kenyans feel their country is being picked on unfairly. `` We were very surprised by all this,'' <PERSON> Afande </PERSON> said.
