<HEAD>Gold Mine Cave-In Kills Three</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TIMMINS, Ontario (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A cave-in in a gold mine shaft killed three miners in this northeastern <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION> city, the mine manager said. The three bodies were brought up from a depth of 1,200 feet about five hours after Monday's accident, said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Perry </PERSON>, general manager of the Placer Dome mine near the <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION> border. One member of a four-man mining crew, who was above ground when the cave-in occurred, had reported his fellow miners missing, <PERSON> Perry </PERSON> said. Union and mine officials said they would conduct separate investigations into the cause of the cave-in. It was the second fatal accident in a year at the mine, which began operating in 1910. A worker was killed in May when he fell down an ore chute.
