<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When the curtain rises on the Metropolitan Opera's two-story new production of `` Salome,'' it looks like a set for a <PERSON> Kurt </PERSON> <PERSON> Weill </PERSON> opera or maybe `` Cabaret.'' It cries out `` German decadence'' in the time the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> came to power. It does n't make `` Salome'' any more universal to set it in the century in which <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Strauss </PERSON> composed it rather than in biblical times, but it works. Even for an audience which has heard `` Salome'' often before, the production and <PERSON> Eva </PERSON> <PERSON> Marton </PERSON> as Salome provided some chilling moments. Miss <PERSON> Marton </PERSON> is exceptional. Her voice soars through dense orchestration. Mature technique gets her there but she keeps her voice sounding young. Salome is young and director <PERSON> Nikolaus </PERSON> <PERSON> Lehnhoff </PERSON> has directed carefully in that direction. Her acting conveys that Salome does n't understand the lust that draws her to <PERSON> John </PERSON> the Baptist When he flings her from him, she has childish tantrums. After <PERSON> John </PERSON> the Baptist is beheaded, <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Marton </PERSON>'s voice becomes mature-sounding and she seems to be bragging about a kinky lust she now does understand. Two or three small excesses could be trimmed so the theatrical experience is n't broken by inappropriate laughter. The stage is slanted but a woman pushed away by a man probably would n't roll over twice from the shove. When Miss <PERSON> Marton </PERSON> starts her dance, she removes the long pink gloves that match her girlish gown and twirls the gloves like a stripper before throwing them to <PERSON> Herod </PERSON>. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Cassilly </PERSON> sounded Wagnerian as <PERSON> Herod </PERSON>, keeping a full voice centered to punch it authoritatively through the large orchestra. <PERSON> Helga </PERSON> <PERSON> Dernesch </PERSON> was glamorous as <PERSON> Salome </PERSON>'s mother, Herodias. <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> sounded very good as <ORGANIZATION> Narraboth </ORGANIZATION>, the young guard captivated by <PERSON> Salome </PERSON>. He replaced <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosenshein </PERSON>, who was ill. The set is like nothing else the Met has seen. The main stage looks like the basement of a castle, with walls of black bricks, a gate at the back and a rectangular hole in the floor, the dungeon where <PERSON> John </PERSON> the Baptist, called <PERSON> Jochanaan </PERSON> in the opera, is kept. <PERSON> Bernd </PERSON> <PERSON> Weikl </PERSON> sounded commanding as <PERSON> Jochanaan </PERSON>. But his standing against the gate, arms outstretched like <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> on the cross, was another effect used too often. Miss <PERSON> Marton </PERSON>'s dance of the seven veils was a success. She began with graceful arm motions and no veils in sight. As she danced, she removed the skirt of her dress and sheer underskirts, throwing them into the dungeon. She finished in a simple white dress. <PERSON> Marek </PERSON> <PERSON> Janowski </PERSON> conducted superbly. <PERSON> Gil </PERSON> <PERSON> Wechsler </PERSON> had spotlights follow principals through the general gloom and put two fixed spotlights on <PERSON> Jochanaan </PERSON>. <PERSON> Lehnhoff </PERSON>, from <LOCATION> Hannover </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, was making his Met directing debut. Set and costume designer <PERSON> Jurgen </PERSON> <PERSON> Rose </PERSON>, a native of Bernburg-Saale, <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, also made his Met debut.
