<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Augusto </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> says that although the constitution prevents him from running for re-election, he will still pick the candidate he wants to succeed him and will not step down as army chief. `` I'm going to tell you soon whom we must support'' in presidential balloting scheduled for Dec. 14, the right-wing general told cheering supporters on Sunday in <LOCATION> Temuco </LOCATION>, 370 miles south of <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION>. `` Let's stay together, let's not quarrel among ourselves,'' the 72-year-old army commander said in his speech carried by <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION> newspapers on Monday. `` We should not yield the field to those other gentlemen'' in the opposition. Congressional elections also will be held Dec. 14. The Temuco speech quickly drew fire from opposition leaders, who called <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>'s remarks a threat to any future elected government. <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> was ending an eight-day tour of southern <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> during which he made clear that he plans to retain a key role in <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> once he steps down from the presidency in March 1990. The 55,000-men army is by far the most powerful of the armed services and the key to <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>'s hold of power for more than 15 years. Under a 1980 military-written constitution, <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> is allowed to remain army commander for eight years after leaving the presidency. He must hand power over on March 11, 1990, to the winner of the December election. <PERSON> Andres </PERSON> <PERSON> Zaldivar </PERSON>, vice president of the centrist <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, said Monday of <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>'s remarks: `` That's unacceptable <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> should leave the army as a gesture of dignity.'' <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> took power in a violent 1973 coup that toppled the elected government of <PERSON> Salvador </PERSON> <PERSON> Allende </PERSON>, a Marxist who died in the takeover. <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> was obliged to call the elections after losing an Oct. 5 referendum, in which he sought voters' approval to remain in power until 1997. After the referendum defeat, the pro-Pinochet forces split. At least two politicians formally announced their candidacies for president and conservative business leaders are actively promoting the nomination of <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>'s 39-year-old finance minister, <PERSON> Hernan </PERSON> <PERSON> Buchi </PERSON>. Several small groups also asked that a formula be found, probably a constitutional amendment, to allow <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> to run. He insists, however, he definitely will not be a candidate. The constitution bars him from running. But <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> has made it clear that he plans to play an active role in the campaign and the election by telling his followers for whom to vote. The opposition says it plans to seek a single presidential candidate. Leaders of a coalition of 17 opposition parties are scheduled to pick the nominee next month among at least four contenders. <PERSON> Patricio </PERSON> <PERSON> Aylwin </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> president, is considered the front-runner. <PERSON> Aylwin </PERSON> is president of the <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION>, the largest opposition party, and was the opposition's chief spokesman during the campaign for the referendum.
