<HEAD>Shares Down in Japan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Share prices plunged at the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday, but the dollar finished higher against the Japanese yen. The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected shares, a 3.69-point winner for a record close of 32,177.08 on Monday, lost 197.00 points, or 0.61 percent, to finish the day's session at 31,980.08. The dollar closed at 127.15 yen, up 1.40 yen from Monday's 125.75-yen finish The currency opened at 126.60 yen and was traded in a range of 126.60-127 .35 yen Dealers said many market participants hesitated to make major moves before Congressional testimony by <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> scheduled for later Tuesday. They added that the dollar moved higher because speculative investors bought up the currency in anticipation of a tighter <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic policy. On the stock exchange, profit-taking erased earlier gains made by the index, which had won about 48.40 points shortly after the market opened for trading. Dealers said many speculative investors backed off in fear that the main market barometer may rise too sharply. Attention focused on medium-sized shares, they said.
