<DATELINE>HANOVER, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In the 1960s, <PERSON> Leo </PERSON> <PERSON> Whalen </PERSON> watched a news report about the home of the nation's 36th president and decided that <PERSON> Lyndon </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>'s ranch needed a few ducks. So he wrote a letter and proposed a trade: mallards to put in the water on <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>'s property in exchange for a Lone Star <ORGANIZATION> LBJ </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ranch </ORGANIZATION> hat. `` It seems that you have a deal,'' <ORGANIZATION> LBJ </ORGANIZATION>'s aide, <PERSON> Earl </PERSON> <PERSON> Deathe </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, replied. The presidential pact was a feather in <PERSON> Whalen </PERSON>'s cap, but no big deal for his <ORGANIZATION> Whistling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, beak broker to the world. The <PERSON> Whalen </PERSON> family is to mallards what the Wrigleys are to gum. Only more so. Each year, 200,000 mallards are born in this town of 1,100, which lies 10 miles east of the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> in the northwestern corner of <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>. They're sold to conservation groups, university researchers, hunting clubs, foreign palaces and even a few restaurants _ around the globe. `` We originally started as a hunting club, but it never really got off the ground,'' said the founder's son, <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Whalen </PERSON>, who shares duck-keeping duties with his sister, <PERSON> Marianne </PERSON> <PERSON> Whalen </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>. `` Dad brought the idea home from <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> after World War II. But at that time we were too far from any major city to draw hunters, so we diversified and simply went into raising the birds,'' he said. Because mallards are the most popular hunting ducks, Whistling Wings stuck with them. `` We've grown up with it,'' says Mrs. <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>, `` and it's grown with us. `` When you pick up the phone you never know who you're going to be talking to. Once it was a caller from <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, inquiring about ducks for Emperor <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>. Chilean officials asked if they could send a plane to get some eggs, and the <ORGANIZATION> Brookfield </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Zoo </ORGANIZATION> in suburban <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> bought a duck each week for an 11-foot anaconda snake. `` It just would n't take anything else,'' said zoo reptile curator <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Pawley </PERSON>. Whistling Wings has 4,000 breeding ducks. Each hen produces at least 40 eggs that hatch in incubators after 27 days. <ORGANIZATION> Ducks </ORGANIZATION> sell for $ 1.55 to $ 15.50 depending on the age of the duck and size of the order. Younger ducks cost less. Mrs. <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> and her brother deal ducks out of a small office in the center of <LOCATION> Hanover </LOCATION>. A few miles south, near the town sign that welcomes travelers to the `` World's Mallard Duck Capital,'' is the farm where ducks are kept in pens during late fall and winter. When the weather turns warm, most newborn mallards are driven to a chain of small, private lakes on 300 hilly acres in <LOCATION> Jo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Daviess </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. `` We want to raise them in their own environment,'' <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Whalen </PERSON> explained as he took a visitor around the scenic duck territory, icy and bare in winter. By truck or plane, they're shipped to 48 states and points beyond _ sometimes unintentionally. `` Mom took some into <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> once for a flight to <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> said. `` The plane was hijacked to <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>. One-thousand birds headed to <LOCATION> Tallahassee </LOCATION> became Cuban ducks.''
