<HEAD>Minor Earthquake Shakes Washington State</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A minor earthquake shook <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> suburbs, but there were no reports of damage, said the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Earthquake </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> here. The quake occurred at 10:48 p.m. PST Monday about 20 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> and registered 3.0 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale, the center said. The quake was felt in the south <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> suburbs of <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Way </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Renton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Enumclaw </LOCATION> and Skyway, the center said. The <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on seismographs. Every increase of one number means a tenfold increase in magnitude. Thus a reading of 7.5 reflects an earthquake 10 times stronger than one of 6.5. An earthquake of 3.5 on the scale can cause slight damage.
