<FIRST>r a PM-BubbleBoy-Anniversary     02-21 0462</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bubble Boy-Anniversary,0476</SECOND>
<HEAD>Five Years After Bubble's Boy Death, Babies With Same Disorder Surviving</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY17 of Feb. 20</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA TOLLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An experimental bone-marrow transplant that ended in death five years ago for <PERSON> David </PERSON>, the `` boy in the plastic bubble,'' is helping other children with the same immune system disorder to survive without isolation. `` His life certainly had an impact on mankind. If only our lives could have as much of an impact,'' said Dr. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Shearer </PERSON>, <PERSON> David </PERSON>'s primary physician at <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Children's Hospital <PERSON> David </PERSON> was born with severe combined immune deficiency syndrome, or SCIDS, a disorder that left him without protection against disease. At the time, children with the disorder died because there was no treatment. Doctors placed <PERSON> David </PERSON> in a clear plastic bubble immediately after birth and increasingly bigger bubbles as he grew to protect him from germs while researchers worked on a treatment. <PERSON> David </PERSON>, whose family name was never released to the public, died Feb. 22, 1984, of blood cancer contracted shortly after he underwent a bone-marrow transplant designed to free him from the bubble. No other child lived like <PERSON> David </PERSON> and, because of the treatment, there has not been another `` bubble boy.'' Today, at <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Children </LOCATION><LOCATION> 's </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>, many children with SCIDS are being treated successfully with the improved transplant treatment, <PERSON> Shearer </PERSON> said. A handful of hospitals across the country also perform the transplant. Gone are the strict sterile conditions that made <PERSON> David </PERSON> a prisoner of his disorder. Children with the condition stay in the hospital before and after transplant. Visitors need only wash their hands and be healthy. SCIDS also is being identified earlier, thanks to pediatricians who are more aware of the disorder. `` When they see children who have unusual infections, they think maybe this child has a similar problem -LRB- to <PERSON> David </PERSON> -RRB-,'' <PERSON> Shearer </PERSON> said. About one out of 100,000 babies have SCIDS. The treatment involves taking about a quart of bone marrow from a donor, either a sibling or a parent, and injecting it into a vein. If the transplant is successful, cells known as lymphocytes in the marrow form the core of a healthy immune system. Sixteen children have been treated at <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Children's in the past five years, including one boy who successfully underwent the procedure while <PERSON> David </PERSON> was dying. Eleven are still alive. Three-month-old <PERSON> Ana </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruth </PERSON> <PERSON> Calderon </PERSON> was released from the hospital three weeks ago after receiving a marrow transplant. `` She is fat and sassy, doing well,'' <PERSON> Shearer </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Shearer </PERSON> said neither he nor <PERSON> David </PERSON>'s parents look back at whether anything could have been done differently. `` They went for a chance at the time when the technology was right,'' the doctor said, `` and for one reason or another, it worked out in a very sad way.''
