<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government freed 50 more detainees today after hunger strikes were halted at two prisons, but scores of detainees continued to fast elsewhere and police said 20 were hospitalized. Law and Order Minister <PERSON> Adriaan </PERSON> <PERSON> Vlok </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> he had signed release warrants for 50 detainees. He did not say how many took part in hunger strikes to demand they be freed or brought to court. About 225 detainees still are refusing food at prisons in the southern cities of <LOCATION> Durban </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pietermaritzburg </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, their lawyers said. Police reported 20 hunger strikers in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> were hospitalized Monday, four days after they and six fellow detainees began fasting. Civil rights lawyers said about 200 detainees in <LOCATION> Durban </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pietermaritzburg </LOCATION> have begun hunger strikes in the past two weeks. <PERSON> Vlok </PERSON> has agreed to meet lawyers for the detainees, but no date has been set. The first wave of hunger strikes started Jan. 23 and involved nearly 300 detainees held without charge in <LOCATION> Port </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Elizabeth </LOCATION> and at Diepkloof Prison outside <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION>. Some detainees at those prisons went three weeks without food then broke their fast after <PERSON> Vlok </PERSON> promised to review their cases and release `` a substantial number.'' Eight detainees were freed Friday. <PERSON> Vlok </PERSON> has won widepsread praise, even from anti-government leaders, for agreeing to meet with lawyers, parents and clergymen representing the hunger strikers. He told <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> he would continue these discussions `` and I trust the entire hunger strike will soon be something of the past.'' The Rev. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Chikane </PERSON>, general secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Churches </ORGANIZATION>, on Monday visited a <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> hospital where some Diepkloof hunger strikers are recovering. He said it was possible the fast would resume if the detainees were dissatisfied about the numbers released in the next two weeks. Many of the hunger strikers have been held more than two years. Under the 32-month-old national state of emergency, police can arrest anyone they believe may be a danger to the public safety. <PERSON> Vlok </PERSON> decides periodically, based on police reports, whether the detainee should remain incarcerated. Detainees do not have to be brought to court and charged, and they can be kept in custody for as long as the government pleases. Monitoring groups say more than 30,000 people, mostly blacks, have been detained during the state of emergency. <PERSON> Vlok </PERSON> has never given a total figure, but he said two weeks ago that there were fewer than 1,000 people in detention at that time.
