countryside, while government troops control major cities. The 1980 revolt occurred two months after Soviet troops intervened to bolster a Marxist government in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>. Soviet soldiers fired on Moslem protesters who emerged from their homes shouting `` God is Great!'' Government officials say dozens of people were killed. Around the city today, business was brisk in some shops but light in others. Some closed for the occasion. Authorities stepped up security around the city, sending more soldiers to marketplaces. <PERSON> Omar </PERSON> said security agents received a tip that guerrillas and sympathizers had stored weapons and explosive devices in a well. He said they searched eight days before finding the arms. Among the weapons were 113 pounds of plastic explosives that agents said came from <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, Chinese-made hand grenades, British mortar shells, Egyptian rockets, Italian fuses for mines, British and Pakistani detonators, Swedish circuit testers, Chinese Kalashnikov rifles, and British pistols. There were also political pamphlets. Officials also showed several fliers they said the guerrillas distributed in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> last week suggesting that rockets attacks were imminent. One, printed in English and the local language <LOCATION> Dari </LOCATION>, said: `` We will contine our Jihad -LRB- holy war -RRB- until the withdrawal of the last Soviet soldier.'' The final Soviet troops, once estimated at more than 100,000 in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, withdrew Wednesday under a U.N.-mediated accord. President <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> has accused <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> of stepping up its supply of weapons to the guerrillas, who have rejected offers of power-sharing and vowed to overthrow the government. Over the weekend, <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> declared a state of emergency and shook up his government to consolidate control.
