ercent of amounts over that. The fee is to reimburse governmental expenses in helping resolve the claims. The government said the <LOCATION> Sperry </LOCATION> corporations owed it $ 42,000. A federal appeals court here ruled last August that the fee is an unconstitutional seizure of private property by the government. `` Whatever -LRB- the fee -RRB- was thought to be, it was a taking of <PERSON> Sperry </PERSON>'s money to help settle the national crisis, a burden the government must bear on behalf of all of us,'' the appeals court said. <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> lawyers, in seeking <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> review, said tens of millions of dollars are at stake. Some $ 12.7 million already has been deducted by the government from awards to successful claimants. The government's appeal said it is reasonable to require those that win claims against <ORGANIZATION> Iran </ORGANIZATION> to defray the $ 4 million the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government spends each year to help operate the <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> claims process. The case is <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Sperry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, 88-952.
