<FIRST>u w PM-Scotus-SummaryTrials     02-21 0548</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Summary Trials,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Rejects Newspapers Open-Trial Plea</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> let stand rulings that the public has no right to attend the so-called `` summary jury trials'' held in some legal disputes. The justices, without comment, rejected arguments by newspapers in three <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> cities that trial judges should be barred from conducting such proceedings in secret. The newspapers' lawyers had asked the high court to rule, for the first time, that the Constitution provides a public right of access to judicial proceedings in civil, or non-criminal, cases. The court in 1980 ruled that the public has a right to attend criminal trials even when defendants object. The justices since have expanded that ruling to cover jury selection and pretrial proceedings in criminal cases. But the court never has ruled that such a right of access exists as well for civil trials and proceedings. The appeal acted on today stems from a 1984 lawsuit by three <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> utilities against <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, over the design and construction of the <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Zimmer </PERSON> Nuclear Power Plant. The suit alleged that <ORGANIZATION> GE </ORGANIZATION> sold the utilties _ <ORGANIZATION> Dayton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Light </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Columbus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Cincinnati </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> _ a nuclear reactor container system it knew was incapable of `` operating in a safe manner.'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Spiegel </PERSON> presided over a summary jury trial in the case, in which lawyers for both sides presented summaries of their evidence. The jury's verdict in such proceedings is advisory and non-binding unless both sides agree otherwise. The verdict is supposed to be a reliable indicator of a full trial's outcome _ sparking attempts to settle so a full trial will not be necessary. Since first introduced in 1980, summary jury trials have been used in at least 65 federal courts in about half the states. In the GE case, the judge ruled that the summary trial would be closed to the public and ordered the parties, lawyers and jurors never to reveal anything that occurred during the proceeding. He also permanently sealed the trial transcript. The <ORGANIZATION> Cincinnati </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>, The Dayton Daily News and The Columbus Dispatch challenged the closure, but the 6th <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> ruled against them last Aug. 18. The appeals court said summary jury trials are more akin to settlement conferences than real trials, and that the public therefore has no right to attend or see the transcript. `` There is no historically recognized of right to summary jury trials in that this mechanism has been in existence for less than a decade,'' the appeals court said, adding, `` There is general agreement that historically settlement techniques are closed procedures.'' In seeking <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> review, lawyers for the three newspapers argued, `` Public confidence will be lost if judges may respond to their expanding dockets by disposing of cases through secret courtroom proceedings and permanent gag orders.'' `` This court can not expect that public confidence, so vital to an effective judiciary, will thrive where judges conduct decisive courtroom proceedings behind closed doors in permanent, court-imposed secrecy,'' the appeal contended. But lawyers for GE discounted what they called the appeal's `` great flourishes of hyperbole,'' and urged the justices to reject it The case is <ORGANIZATION> Cincinnati </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> vs. GE, 88-813.
</TEXT>
