<HEAD>Guerrillas Attack Army Brigade In Capital, Civilians Killed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Leftist guerrillas bombed the headquarters of an army brigade in the capital today, killing two civilians and wounding three others, authorities said. Rebels also used rocket-propelled grenades and rifle fire in a pre-dawn attack on a military engineers' base in <LOCATION> Zacatecoluca </LOCATION>, 35 miles southeast of the capital. Radio reports said the assault killed three soldiers. The rebel attack on the 1st army brigade base, which killed an elderly couple who live nearby, was the fifth since November on a major military installation in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>. As in the earlier attacks, guerrillas used pickup trucks fitted with a catapult-like device to launch the bombs against the 1st brigade. The detonation of one explosive charge launches the bombs and simultaneously blows up the vehicle. Two vehicles exploded today, killing <PERSON> Pedro </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON>, about 70 years old, and his wife <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> Teresa </PERSON>, about 65. <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON>'s body lay on the sidewalk in front of his home an hour after the vehicle parked in front of it exploded. Mrs. <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON>, whose legs were blown off by the blast, died on the way to the hospital, said Col. <PERSON> Orlando </PERSON> <PERSON> Zepeda </PERSON>, who commands the 4,000-troop brigade. Three civilians were wounded by the explosions, <PERSON> Zepeda </PERSON> said. The bombs launched by the vehicles did not fall inside the grounds of the 1st brigade, he said. Journalists were denied entry to the installation to verify the report. The explosions damaged about 10 homes, breaking windows, gouging walls and blowing doors off hinges. In <LOCATION> Zacatecoluca </LOCATION>, Marxist-led guerrillas and soldiers battled for three hours near the headquarters of the <ORGANIZATION> Detachment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Military </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineers </ORGA