<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Copyright     02-21 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Copyright,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Turns Away Virginia Case On Federal Copyright Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today refused to let states and state agencies be sued for alleged violations of federal copyright law. The court, without comment, turned away a <LOCATION> Radford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, case that highlighted a conflict between the Constitution's 11th Amendment shielding states from federal lawsuits and copyright law requiring all suits be filed in federal court. Photographer <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> sued <ORGANIZATION> Radford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, a state-run school, and some school officials over the unauthorized use in 1982 of copyright photographs. A federal trial judge dismissed the school and its officials as defendants, ruling that the 11th Amendment protects them against such suits. The 4th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> upheld the dismissal by a 2-1 vote last July 20. The appeals court noted a 1985 <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decision that `` <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> may abrogate the states' constitutionally secured immunity from suit in federal court only making its intention unmistakably clear in the language of the statute.'' <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> did not do so in passing the Copyright Act of 1976, the appeals court said. In the appeal acted on today, lawyers for <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> argued that the 4th Circuit court misinterpreted the 1976 copyright law. They said the law was intended to make states generally accountable for copyright violations. `` Because the jurisdiction of the federal courts is exclusive -LRB- in copyright cases -RRB- the effect of the 11th Amendment defense is not simply to relegate the injured party to a suit in state court but to deny any damage recovery at all against state infringers,'' the appeal said. The <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishers </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Presses </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intellectual </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Property </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> sided with <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> in `` friend of the court'' briefs. `` Whenever the 11th Amendment has previously been found to preclude federal court jurisdiction some other forum has been available,'' one of those briefs told the justices. `` For -LRB- <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> -RRB- and all others holding copyrights, however, no relief can be sought in state courts.'' The case is <ORGANIZATION> Anderson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Photography </ORGANIZATION> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Radford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, 88-651.
