<DATELINE>PORT ARTHUR, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 About 7,000 people returned to their homes today after they had been evacuated because of a stinking gas from a refinery's leaking crude oil tank, police said. The evacuation order was lifted at 5:30 a.m., police officer <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Gillen </PERSON> said. `` All the roads are reopened. Everything is back to normal as it was before the leak.'' The gas, which escaped Monday from a leaking tank at a <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> refinery, contained hydrogen sulfide, a flammable, poisonous chemical that smells like rotten eggs. The leak, first discovered in the afternoon, was not considered a serious health threat, but at least 24 people were examined at local hospitals, officials said. No serious injuries were reported. An estimated 5,000 to 7,000 people were asked to leave their homes in this coastal city near the <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> border, and about 3,000 stayed in emergency shelters overnight, said police Sgt. <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Blanton </PERSON>. The rest found lodging on their own. Police barricaded a 17-by-14-block area in the western portion of the heavily industrial city. `` We've had some real bad fires at these plants where people were injured and killed, but even then we never had an evacuation of this magnitude and I've been here 28 years,'' said police Sgt. <PERSON> Cedric </PERSON> <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON>. `` We decided to evacuate the entire area simply as a safety precaution,'' he added. `` There are a lot of elderly people who live in that particular area and there are two or three -LRB- public -RRB- housting complexes.'' <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> officials said they had been monitoring air quality in the area of the leak since early Monday afternoon, and described the gaseous release as carrying a miminum risk but a terrible odor. `` Most crude oils in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> have sulphur in them, and that means their gas contains hydrogen sulfide, which is listed as one of the hazardous chemicals,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Art </PERSON> <PERSON> Spencer </PERSON>. `` We're doing continuous monitoring and we're finding that there's nothing there that is hazardous to health and we're also finding that the hydrocarbon smell in the air is lessening,'' <PERSON> Spencer </PERSON> said. `` But the odor got so strong that the city emergency response unit decided to go ahead and evacuate people downwind of it.'' <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Jody </PERSON> <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> said doctors treated 20 people, many of whom complained of headaches, watery eyes or breathing difficulties. Four patients also were treated at Doctors Hospital. A <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> employee discovered the leak around 1:30 p.m. Monday and reported it around the same time that the first calls began arriving at police headquarters, officials said. <PERSON> Spencer </PERSON> said the leaking tank has a capacity of about 300,000 gallons, but its exact content was not known because it was connected to an automatic pump that fed into a refining unit. Crews were using vacuum trucks this morning to remove the spilled crude from a ditch surrounding the tank. <PERSON> Spencer </PERSON> estimated the task could take two or three days to complete.
