<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today rejected an appeal by mining companies seeking an exemption from federal environmental rules for certain hazardous wastes. The court, without comment, let stand a ruling that the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> must regulate the wastes. The <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> ruled last July that a 1980 federal law exempting some `` high volume, low hazard'' mining wastes from environmental rules does not apply to six types of waste produced from smelting. The appeals court said the exemption does not apply to six types of dust, sludge and other waste from the smelting of copper, lead, zinc, aluminum, ferrochromium and ferrochromium-silicon. In a victory for environmental groups, the appeals court overturned an <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> decision and ordered the agency to apply hazardous-waste rules to the six types of smelter waste. The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mining </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Aluminum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Kennecott </ORGANIZATION> said the 1980 law was intended to apply to `` all mining industry processing wastes.'' The case is <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mining </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> vs. Environmental Defense Fund, 88-848.
