he <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Poverty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, which represented Person, filed the criminal contempt complaint and, in an unusual development, acted as prosecutor in the contempt proceeding for about two months. In June 1986, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney's office in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> was placed in charge of the case. <PERSON> Dees </PERSON> was allowed to continue as an assistant to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney's office in prosecuting the complaint. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> was convicted of criminal contempt after a jury heard testimony that his ultimate goal was the armed overthrow of the government. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said his rights were violated for a number of reasons. He argued that <PERSON> Dees </PERSON> continued to be in charge of the prosecution after June 1986 and was biased against him. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> also said all blacks should have been barred as prospective jurors because they stood to benefit from the court order <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> was charged with violating. The 4th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> upheld his conviction last August. The appeals court said there was adequate evidence that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney's office, and not <PERSON> Dees </PERSON>, was in control of the case. The appeals court also said <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> failed to show that no black could serve as an impartial juror in a case involving a white supremacist. The case is <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> vs. Person, 88-792.
