 the seizure based on a judgment that two items sold by the store were obscene. The law allows prosecutors `` to cast wide nets and seize ... the obscene, those non-obscene yet sexually explicit -LRB- items -RRB-, even those devoid of sexual reference,'' <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> said. The law was used in March 1984 against three <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wayne </LOCATION> bookstores selling sexually explict material. Law enforcement officials padlocked the stores and seized all inventory. The three <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wayne </LOCATION> stores were allowed to reopen in April 1985. But only one, <ORGANIZATION> Fort </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wayne </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Books </ORGANIZATION>, remains in business. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today also upheld rulings that permit the <LOCATION> Howard </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ind. </LOCATION>, sheriff's office to charge <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Sappenfield </PERSON> with distributing obscene material and violating the state RICO law. That case has yet to go trial. The cases are <ORGANIZATION> Fort </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wayne </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Books </ORGANIZATION> vs. <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, 87-470, and <LOCATION> Sappenfield </LOCATION> vs. <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, 87-614.
