<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Patent Law,000</SECOND>
<HEAD>MH</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 States may not offer the equivalent of patent protection for utilitarian and design ideas left unprotected by federal law, the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled unanimously today. The justices killed a lawsuit in which a <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> boat manufacturer charged that its design for a fiberglass recreational boat was duplicated illegally by a competitor. The court said only <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, and not individual states, can decide at some future date to protect certain industrial design ideas. `` It is for <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to determine if the present system of design and utility patents is ineffectual in promoting the useful arts in the context of industrial design,'' Justice <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Day </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> wrote for the court. She said a <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> law that would have protected the boat manufacturer's design `` conflicts with the strong federal policy favoring free competition in ideas which do not merit patent protection.'' <ORGANIZATION> Bonito </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boats </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in 1976 developed an original hull design that was marketed as model 5VBR. A hardwood model was created from engineering drawings, and the model was then sprayed with fiberglass to create a mold. The mold then was used to produce the finished fiberglass boats for sale. No patent was obtained for the utilitarian or design aspects of the hull, or for the process by which the hull was manufactured. After the model 5VBR proved a marketing success, the <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> enacted a law that, in effect, gave <ORGANIZATION> Bonita </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boats </ORGANIZATION> a state-level monopoly for making hulls that way. Bonito Boats later invoked the state law in suing Thunder Craft Boats for allegedly using the same process. A <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> trial judge, upheld by the state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, threw out the lawsuit after ruling that the state law giving protection to Bonito Boats' creativity impermissibly conflicts with federal patent law Today's decision upheld the state court rulings. `` <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has considered extending various forms of limited protection to industrial design either through the copyright laws or by relaxing the restrictions on the availability of design patents,'' <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> noted. `` <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> explicitly refused to take this step in the copyright laws, and despite sustained criticism for a number of years it has declined to alter the patent protections presently available for industrial design,'' she said. The case is Bonito Boats vs. Thunder Craft Boats, 87-1346.
