<HEAD>Supreme Court Rules States Cannot Exempt Religious Writings from
Sales Tax</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled today that states may not give preferential treatment to religious publications by exempting them from sales taxes imposed on other books, newspapers and magazines. By a 6-3 vote, the justices said a now-defunct <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> statute violated the Constitution. The decision presumably will force the state to give sales tax refunds to non-religious publications or impose the levy against religious organizations that were exempt. Five justices _ <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON>, <PERSON> Thurgood </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON>, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>, <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Blackmun </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Day </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> _ said the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> law violated the Constitution's required separation of church and state. Justice <PERSON> Byron </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON> said the law violated free-press guarantees in the Constitution by taxing non-religious publications while exempting others solely on the basis of religious content. Dissenting were Chief Justice <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rehnquist </PERSON> and <PERSON> Justices </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonin </PERSON> <PERSON> Scalia </PERSON> and <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>. <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON>, writing only for himself, <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> and <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>, said <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>'s previous sales tax exemption for religious publications `` lacks a secular objective'' and `` effectively endorses religious belief.'' Moreover, <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> said, nothing in the Constitution's guarantee of the free exercise of religion bars states from imposing such taxes on religious periodicals. In a separate concurring opinion, <PERSON> Blackmun </PERSON> and <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> said while the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> law violates the separation of church and state, some exemptions for religious publications could be constitutional. `` For example,'' said <PERSON> Blackmun </PERSON> in an opinion joined by <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON>, `` a state statute might exempt the sale not only of religious literature distributed by a religious organization but also of philosophical literature distributed by non-religious organizations devoted to such matters of conscience as life and death, good and evil, being and non-being, right and wrong.'' In a dissenting opinion joined by <PERSON> Rehnquist </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, <PERSON> Scalia </PERSON> said the ruling appears to topple exemptions for religious publications granted by many other states. `` In short, religious tax exemptions of the type the court invalidates today permeate the state and federal -LRB- legal -RRB- codes and have done so for many years,'' <PERSON> Scalia </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> imposed a sales tax on books and periodicals from October 1984 through October 1987. But the law exempted `` periodicals published or distributed by a religious faith and that consist wholly of writings promulgating the teaching of the faith.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> revoked the sales tax on all books and periodicals in October 1987. <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monthly </ORGANIZATION>, a general interest magazine with a circulation of about 280,000, challenged the exemption for religious publications after it paid more than $ 149,000 in sales taxes in 1985. The magazine is seeking a refund of the money. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in 1987 struck down an <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> tax imposed on sales of general interest magazines but exempted newspapers and religious, professional, trade and sports magazines. The court in that case said states have a heavy burden of proof to justify taxing publications based on their content. The <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> law presented a different situation: everything but religious publications had been taxed. The case acted on today is <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Monthly vs. <PERSON> Bullock </PERSON>, 87-1245.
