<FIRST>u w PM-Scotus-Postal     02-21 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Postal,630</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Postal workers accused of traffic violations must stand trial in state courts, a unanimous <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled today. The decision limits the federal government's power to block some state prosecutions of federal workers. The justices ordered two <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> mail carriers to stand trial in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> state courts. Both cases stem from traffic accidents in <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Clara </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. In one, <PERSON> Kathryn </PERSON> <PERSON> Isabella </PERSON> <PERSON> Mesa </PERSON> was accused of misdemeanor-manslaughter after her mail truck collided with and killed a bicyclist. In the other, <PERSON> Shabbir </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ebrahim </PERSON> was charged with speeding and failing to yield after his mail truck collided with a police car. Both defendants succeeded in tranferring their cases to a federal court. But the 9th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> in 1987 sent the cases back to the state courts. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today upheld the appeals court ruling. Justice <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Day </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON>, writing for the court, rejected <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> arguments that permitting state prosecutions in such cases could interfere with federal officials in performance of their duties. Only if a federal issue is directly at stake may a prosecution be shifted to federal court, <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> said. She also noted that transferring cases like traffic violations to federal court would impose heavy burdens on local state prosecutors. `` We can discern no federal interest in potentially forcing local district attorneys to choose between prosecuting traffic violations hundreds of miles from the municipality in which the violations occurred or abandoning those prosecutions,'' <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> said. A federal law providing for removal of states cases to federal court was enacted in response to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>'s opposition to a trade embargo declared during the War of 1812 between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. Federal customs officials were given authority then to board vessels in order to collect duties, assuring they would avoid prosecution in state courts for any alleged misconduct in the performance of their duties. The 9th Circuit court had noted that in the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> case there was no claim by the mail carriers that their allegedly illegal conduct was justified by the duties they were performing. The case is <LOCATION> Mesa </LOCATION> vs. <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, 87-1206.
