<HEAD>President's Comments in Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here, at a glance, are the main topics President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> covered in his news conference Tuesday:
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>IRAN-RUSDIE</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> sharply criticized the <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> for `` exhorting people to go out and commit murder'' against <PERSON> Salman </PERSON> <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON>, author of `` Satanic Verses.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said that `` however offensive that book may be, inciting murder and offering rewards for its perpetraton are deeply offensive to the norms of civilized behavior.'' He warned that, `` In the light of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s incitement, should any action be taken against <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> interests, the government of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> can expect to be held accountable.'' He supported the European Community's unified stance against <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s threats, and said he would discuss the possibility of sanctions with the president of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and other leaders in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>MIDDLE EAST</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The president said the Soviets' role in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> `` should be a limited role, and I think that's what it's going to be.'' He said he was not going to be `` stampeded'' into pressing ahead on <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> policy simply because Soviet Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> is visiting the region. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy is `` to encourage discussions between King <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> -LRB- of <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> -RRB- and the Israelis and to build on the progress that has been made already.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>TOWER</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> reaffirmed his support for <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Tower </PERSON>, saying an <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> report had `` gunned down'' allegations of misconduct against the nominee for secretary of defense. He said, `` Anybody that's been through this ordeal will be stronger, not weaker'' in running the Pentagon.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>DAVID DUKE</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The president said it may have been `` improper or overkill'' for him to urge <LOCATION> Metairie </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> La. </LOCATION>, voters to reject former <PERSON> Ku </PERSON> <PERSON> Klux </PERSON> <PERSON> Klan </PERSON> leader <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Duke </PERSON>'s bid for a seat in the state house as a Republican. The voters who elected <PERSON> Duke </PERSON> may have resented the intervention, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said, but <PERSON> Duke </PERSON>'s record `` is one of racism and bigotry and, I'm sorry, I just felt I had to speak out.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>STAR WARS</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said he was `` not ruling anything in or out'' on the Strategic Defense Initiative, popularly known as Star Wars, but the administration has `` some tough choices'' ahead on defense. He reiterated his support for the principle of SDI, but said he was not in favor of `` premature deployment'' and would not close or open any doors until a review of overall defense policy is completed.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>URBAN VIOLENCE</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The president said the federal government has a responsibility to help curb violence in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, and across the nation, but he rejected stiffer gun controls. He said his forthcoming anti-drug program will address his campaign promises to get tough on criminals and build more prisons. He said he wants to enforce `` the laws that are already on the books about automated AK-47s coming into this country.'' He said he wants to help the police `` who are out there on the line all the time,'' but he also wants `` to be the president that protects the rights of people to have arms.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>JAPAN</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> defended Japanese investment in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, saying it is only the third-largest foreign investor behind <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>. He said the Japanese and other foreign investors are helping the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> finance its `` horrendous deficits,'' and it is important to keep <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> markets open even as it presses for `` more openness for American investors in other countries.'' He promised to exercise his responsibility to protect <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> technology and national security.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>PARTY SWITCH</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> welcomed the defection of Rep. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> from the Democratic to the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, saying the switch `` is good news for our party not only in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, not only in the South, but nationally.''
