<HEAD>Supreme Court Orders Tougher Pension Plan Reviews</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today told federal judges to be tougher in second-guessing decisions by pension and welfare plans that deny benefits to workers. In ruling unanimously in a case involving the <ORGANIZATION> Firestone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Rubber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the justices said federal judges must evaluate such cases just as if the pension and welfare plan officials had not yet made any decision. Some federal courts instead have been employing a less stringent standard of review _ generally not disturbing decisions by plan officials unless they are found to be `` arbitrary or capricious.'' The dispute ruled on today stemmed from Firestone's selling its plastics division in 1980 to <ORGANIZATION> Occidental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. The sale affected some 500 workers at Firestone plants in <LOCATION> Pottstown </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Caldwell </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Perryville </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Salisbury </PERSON>, Md.; and <LOCATION> Baton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rouge </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> La </LOCATION>. Nearly all the workers were given the opportunity to keep their jobs under the new ownership, and most accepted. Some workers sought certain benefits from <LOCATION> Firestone </LOCATION>, including early retirement and severance pay, that were included in the three Firestone welfare and pension plans. The company denied the benefits. It also refused to release information about the benefit plans to workers who sought it, on grounds that the workers no longer were employed by <PERSON> Firestone </PERSON> and no longer participants in the plans. The workers sued, charging Firestone with violating the federal Employee Retirement and Income Security Act of 1974 -LRB- ERISA -RRB-. A federal judge threw out the suit, ruling that <PERSON> Firestone </PERSON> did not act in an arbitrary or capricious manner. But the 3rd U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> reinstated the suit. The appeals court said workers' claims must be examined more closely in such cases. Writing for the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today, Justice <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Day </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> said the appeals court was right. <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> said the more stringent standard of judicial review should apply unless the plan gives its administrator or other officials `` the discretionary authority to determine eligibility for benefits or to construe the terms of the plan.'' The justices told the 3rd Circuit court to restudy the issue of whether the workers seeking information about the welfare and pension plans from Firestone qualify as `` participants'' who are entitled under ERISA to such information. The case is Firestone vs. <PERSON> Bruch </PERSON>, 87-1054.
