<HEAD>Bush Puts War Behind Him As He Heads To Japan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s journey to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> will take him inexorably down a path of war memories punctuated by visions of being shot down at sea and losing two <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> buddies in combat. But if attending Emperor <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON>'s funeral on Friday presents a painful reminder of the war with <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is n't saying so. `` I'm doing what's right,'' he said recently. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> aviator whose plane was shot down over the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> by the Japanese in 1944, said, `` We have a good relationship with <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. I want to see it even better. And this does n't concern me a bit. And you're talking to a person who was in combat in World War II. I feel you look ahead, not always look back. You do what's right `` It's the right thing to do.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> visited <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> twice as vice president, in 1982 and 1984. In his 1987 autobiography, `` Looking Forward,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> shows little reluctance to talk about what happened Sept. 2, 1944. The young <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> officer and two other crew members _ gunnery officer <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> `` </PERSON> <PERSON> Ted </PERSON><PERSON> '' </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON> and radioman-tailgunner <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Delaney </PERSON> _ had taken off in a TBM Avenger on a mission to knock out a Japanese radio facility on <LOCATION> Chichi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jima </LOCATION>, one of three islands in the <PERSON> Bonin </PERSON> chain about 600 miles from <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> described in graphic detail how his plane was blown from the sky and how he managed to ride a torn parachute to the water, ultimately to be picked up by a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> rescue ship, the USS Finback. As he neared the water, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> wrote, `` I looked around for <PERSON> Delaney </PERSON> and <PERSON> White </PERSON>, but the only thing in sight was my parachute drfiting away.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> wrote about the letter he sent his parents six days after his rescue, in which he `` described my feelings at the time.'' `` I try to think about it as little as possible,'' he wrote in the book. `` Yet, I can not get those two out of my mind. ... I know I wo n't be able to shake the memory of this incident and I do n't believe I want to completely. Two days before his inauguration Jan. 20, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was reunited with about three dozen of his war buddies, hosting a nostaligic party for surviving fellow pilots, radiomen and gunners and sharing remembrances with them. In a recent telephone interview from his home in <LOCATION> Rogers </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ark. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Kohler </PERSON>, the submarine torpedoman who helped pull <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> from his bobbing life raft, said, `` I think he feels the need to go there for the total relationship between their country and our country. They're a major entity in the world economy.'' <PERSON> Kohler </PERSON>, who is 64, like <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, said he shares the president's view that `` you should forgive and forget. ... I do n't know what part <PERSON> Hirohito </PERSON> had in running the country into war, but, believe me, I think most people in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> today want to forget about the war.'' <PERSON> Kohler </PERSON> added, `` I know there are other people'' in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> `` who have strong feelings the other way.'' Former Sen. <PERSON> Jeremiah </PERSON> <PERSON> Denton </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Ala </LOCATION>., who was a North Vietnamese prisoner of war for eight years, described <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> as `` a giant of a man'' who wants to avoid showing any feeling of vindictiveness toward the Japanese <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is traveling to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> with an interest in `` the commonality of humankind'' and `` with altruism toward his fellow man,'' <PERSON> Denton </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. `` He seems to understand the Japanese people and the Japanese people understand him,'' said <PERSON> Denton </PERSON>. <PERSON> Denton </PERSON> said that while he has not returned to <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, he believes that Americans caught in wars seldom hold lingering bitterness toward the people of a nation that has warred against the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` I feel very lovingly frustrated toward the people of <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>,'' he said. A presidential scholar at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Virginia </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Sabato </PERSON>, said that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> `` is in the noblesse oblige tradition and part of noblesse oblige is sublimating oneself to the common good.'' `` My personal feeling is that if he does have lingering bitterness; he's suppressed it,'' <PERSON> Sabato </PERSON> said. `` He's going to be busy having meetings with world leaders. He really wo n't have that much time to concentrate on the personal aspect of it. He'll be so busy that I do n't think he'll have much time for personal reflection.''
