<HEAD>Supreme Court Limits Damages in Georgia Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, in a case involving alleged fraud in a 20-year-old business merger, today limited the ability of people to seek additional damages after winning a lawsuit. The 9-0 ruling in a case from <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> restricts the ability of purported fraud victims to sue a leading accounting firm. The case arose out of the 1969 merger of <ORGANIZATION> Cavalier </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bag </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and E.T. <ORGANIZATION> Barwick </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. The owners of Cavalier Bag _ <PERSON> Myles </PERSON>, <PERSON> Guy-Kenneth </PERSON> and <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Osterneck </PERSON> _ charged in a 1975 lawsuit that the financial health of <ORGANIZATION> Barwick </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> was overstated. The Osternecks sued <ORGANIZATION> Barwick </ORGANIZATION> officials and <ORGANIZATION> Ernst </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Whinney </ORGANIZATION>, an accounting firm that had prepared the allegedly inflated financial statements. After nearly 10 years of pre-trial maneuvering, the case went to trial in 1984 and the <LOCATION> Barwick </LOCATION> company and its offficials were ordered to pay the Osternecks more than $ 2.6 million in damages plus $ 946,000 in interest. But the <PERSON> Osternecks </PERSON> lost their case against <ORGANIZATION> Ernst </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <LOCATION> Whinney </LOCATION>. They then appealed, seeking to revive the case against the accounting firm. That appeal was filed at the same time that the Osternecks' request for interest payments against the <ORGANIZATION> Barwick </ORGANIZATION> officials was pending in court. The 11th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> ruled that the Osternecks' bid for damages against the accounting firm must be treated as a motion to amend the original judgment that the <PERSON> Osternecks </PERSON> had won Therefore, the appeals court barred the Osternecks from pursuing a separate appeal against <ORGANIZATION> Ernst </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Whinney while at the same time they were seeking additional interest payments against the <ORGANIZATION> Barwick </ORGANIZATION> officials. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today upheld the appeals court ruling. Justice <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, writing for the court, said handling appeals in this manner helps avoid piecemeal appellate court review of lower court judgments. The case is Osterneck vs. <ORGANIZATION> Ernst </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <LOCATION> Whinney </LOCATION>. 87-1201.
