<HEAD>Court Gives Lawyers Extra Fee in Louisiana Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A unanimous <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today gave lawyers added incentive _ the possibility of bigger-than-bargained-for legal fees _ to represent those who claim their civil rights were violated. The court ruled in a <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> case that the losing side in some civil rights lawsuits may be forced to pay the winning side's lawyers more than the lawyers originally had sought The normal rule in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> courts is that each side pays its own lawyers. But <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has altered that rule in about 200 fee-shifting laws, and allowed the winning side to collect its lawyer fees from the losing side. Most notably, such fee awards are available to people who successfully sue over civil rights violations. <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Blanchard </PERSON>, who said he was assaulted without provocation by a <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Martin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parish </ORGANIZATION> sheriff's deputy, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Bergeron </PERSON>, was awarded $ 10,000 in damages by a federal jury. The presiding judge also awarded <PERSON> Blanchard </PERSON> $ 7,500 in lawyer fees, which <PERSON> Bergeron </PERSON> was ordered to pay. But the 5th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> reduced the lawyer-fee award to $ 4,000 after noting that <PERSON> Blanchard </PERSON> and his lawyer had a contingency-fee agreement in which the lawyer was to get 40 percent of any damage award. The appeals court said the 40 percent contingency agreement effectively placed a cap on any lawyer-fee award that could be made. Writing for the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today, Justice <PERSON> Byron </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON> said no such cap exists. `` If a contingent fee agreement were to govern as a strict limitation on the award of attorney's fees, an undesirable emphasis might be placed on the importance of the recovery of damages in civil rights litigation,'' <PERSON> White </PERSON> said. `` The intention of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>,'' he said, `` was to encourage successful civil rights litigation, not to create a special incentive to prove damages and shortchange efforts to seek effective injunctive or declaratory relief.'' The justices told the <ORGANIZATION> 5th </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> court </ORGANIZATION> to reconsider its lawyer-fee award ruling in <PERSON> Blanchard </PERSON>'s case. The case is <PERSON> Blanchard </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Bergeron </PERSON>, 87-1485.
