<BYLINE>By F.N. D'ALESSIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A judge today recommended that <ORGANIZATION> Amoco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> be ordered to pay about $ 115 million to <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and nearly 90 French citizens or businesses damaged by millions of gallons of oil spilled in a 1978 supertanker accident. Retired <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> McGarr </PERSON>, sitting as a special master, recommended an increase of about $ 30 million in his original $ 85.2 million judgment against the oil company. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Norgle </PERSON> will enter a final judgment. Virtually all parties to the case had asked <PERSON> McGarr </PERSON> to reconsider his January 1988 decision, issued before his retirement as a federal judge. <ORGANIZATION> Amoco </ORGANIZATION> and the French plaintiffs immediately indicated they were likely to appeal today's ruling. `` A lot of people wo n't be happy. The recommendation is a mixed bag. But the oyster growers, for one, will be pleased. They're in line for the biggest revision,'' said attorney <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> <PERSON> Marwedel </PERSON>, who represented a number of oyster syndicates, two French regions and a number of other plaintiffs affected by the spill from the <ORGANIZATION> Amoco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cadiz </ORGANIZATION> supertanker. `` It's a very conservative, traditional opinion,'' <PERSON> Marwedel </PERSON> said. `` Things like the loss of enjoyment and environmental claims were not given the consideration we had sought.'' <ORGANIZATION> Amoco </ORGANIZATION> attorney <PERSON> Franck </PERSON> <PERSON> Cicero </PERSON> said the company was pleased with <PERSON> McGarr </PERSON>'s recommendation. ` If you look at the total awarded so far, they've only got about 3 percent of what they originally claimed,'' <PERSON> Cicero </PERSON> said. `` The judge indicated again he thought they were overreaching and there were some duplicate claims.'' <PERSON> Cicero </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Amoco </ORGANIZATION> is proceeding with litigation against the Spanish builder of the <ORGANIZATION> Amoco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cadiz </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Astilleros </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Espanoles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> S.A </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Amoco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cadiz </ORGANIZATION> ran aground two miles off the <LOCATION> Brittany </LOCATION> coast March 16, 1978. The huge tanker, which had lost the use of its rudder, had been under tow through the English Channel by a German-owned tug when the towlines snapped in hurricane-force winds and heavy seas. The Liberian-registered supertanker carried 223,000 tons, or 68 million gallons, of mostly Iranian light crude oil valued at $ 24 million. The spill, the largest ever from a tanker, caused an oil slick more than 10 miles across and 80 miles long. The plaintiffs include more than 90 villages from <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>'s Brittany coast, groups of oystermen and fishermen, property owners and environmentalists They had initially sought more than $ 1.1 billion in damages.
