<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A judge ruled Tuesday that the jurors selected to try mob boss <PERSON> Nicodemo </PERSON> `` Little Nicky'' <PERSON> Scarfo </PERSON> and eight associates in a 1985 rubout will be sequestered, but their names will not be kept secret. The 59-year-old <PERSON> Scarfo </PERSON> and his co-defendants are accused of plotting and carrying out the slaying of <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> `` Frankie Flowers'' <PERSON> D'Alfonso </PERSON>, who was gunned down on a street near his home. Detectives said <PERSON> D'Alfonso </PERSON> had showed `` disrespect'' to <PERSON> Scarfo </PERSON> by joining a rival mob faction. <PERSON> Scarfo </PERSON> could be sentenced to death if convicted. He was convicted last year in a federal racketeering conspiracy case of running the <LOCATION> Philadelphia-South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> Mafia from his <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> home. Assistant District Attorney <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> on Tuesday sought to have the names and addresses of all prospective jurors kept anonymous, but Common Pleas Judge <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> refused. `` He found no evidence that jurors would be threatened if their identity was known,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinsky </PERSON>, an attorney for one of <PERSON> Scarfo </PERSON>'s co-defendants. The judge ruled, however, that the 12 jurors and six alternates, when chosen, will be sequestered in a hotel. Jury selection is expected to take two weeks. <PERSON> Scarfo </PERSON> has been in jail since 1987 and is serving a 14-year sentence for conspiring to extort $ 1 million from a developer. He was acquitted in May of ordering the assassination of a rival and awaits sentencing in the racketeering case.
