<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS first item to delete reference to conviction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here, at-a-glance, are highlights of the major actions taken Tuesday by the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. PORNOGRAPHY The court ruled that states may use anti-racketeering laws to fight pornography, but invoked free-speech rights to ban the states from seizing before trial the contents of adult bookstores. The justices said authorities unlawfully seized the contents of a <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wayne </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ind. </LOCATION>, bookstore before any materials in the store were judged obscene at a trial. But by a 6-3 vote, the justices said prosecutors still may use the state's anti-racketeering law to renew the obscenity case. The cases are <ORGANIZATION> Fort </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wayne </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Books </ORGANIZATION> vs. <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, 87-470, and <LOCATION> Sappenfield </LOCATION> vs. <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, 87-614. RELIGIOUS BOOKS The court ruled that states may not give preferential treatment to religious ublications by exempting them from sales taxes imposed on other books, newspapers and magazines. By a 6-3 vote, the justices said a now-defunct <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> statute violated the Constitution. The decision presumably will force the state to give sales tax refunds to non-religious publications or impose the levy against religious organizations that were exempt. The case is <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Monthly vs. <PERSON> Bullock </PERSON>, 87-1245. SUMMARY TRIALS The court let stand rulings that the public has no right to attend the so-called `` summary jury trials'' held in some legal disputes. The justices, without comment, rejected arguments by newspapers in three <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> cities that trial judges should be barred from conducting such proceedings in secret. The newspapers' lawyers had asked the high court to rule, for the first time, that the Constitution provides a public right of access to judicial proceedings in civil, or non-criminal, cases. The case is <ORGANIZATION> Cincinnati </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> vs. GE, 88-813. EVANGELISTS Television evangelist <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Swaggart </PERSON> failed in his bid to kill a $ 90 million lawsuit by a defrocked evangelist who <PERSON> Swaggart </PERSON> accused of adultery in 1986. The court, without comment, rejected arguments that <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorman </PERSON>'s suit against <PERSON> Swaggart </PERSON> and others unconstitutionally entangles <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> state courts in matters of church doctrine and discipline. The cases are <PERSON> Swaggart </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Adler </PERSON>, 88-1080, and Treeby vs. <PERSON> Gorman </PERSON>, 88-1058. FREEDOM OF EXPRESSION The court refused to reinstate the pandering conviction of a <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> movie producer who hired actors to peform sex acts in a pornographic film. The justices, without comment, let stand a <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling that <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Freeman </PERSON>'s conviction on charges of procuring people for purposes of prostitution violated his freedom of expression. The cases are <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> vs. <PERSON> Freeman </PERSON>, 88-1054, and <PERSON> Applegate </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Freeman </PERSON>, 88-1050. ABORTION The court allowed <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> to begin enforcing a 1986 abortion law that included provisions for parental notification. The justices, without comment, turned down an emergency request by `` pro-choice'' advocates seeking to block the law until a federal appeals court rules on its constitutionality. The case is <PERSON> Eubanks </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Wilkinson </PERSON>, A-582. <LOCATION> IRAN </LOCATION> ASSETS The court agreed to referee a dispute between the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government and American businesses stemming from the 1981 settlement of the <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> hostage crisis. The court said it will review a ruling that businesses recovering money from <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s government do not have to pay a portion of it to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government. The case is <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Sperry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, 88-952. FREEDOM OF INFORMATION While agreeing to keep the identities of the legal combatants a secret, the court voted to resolve a significant dispute over the Freedom of Information Act. The justices said they will decide whether a government law enforcement agency must surrender to a government contractor being investigated for possible fraud certain documents received from another agency. Much of the case is cloaked in secrecy _ including the identity of the contractor and the government agencies involved _ presumably to protect the contractor's reputation. The case is <ORGANIZATION> John </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Doe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> vs. <ORGANIZATION> John </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Doe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, 88-1083. ANIMAL DRUGS The court allowed the <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> to impose strict controls on the use of drugs by veterinarians for `` experimental'' treatment of some animal diseases. The court, without comment, rejected arguments by an <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> drug distributing company that the government wrongly is interfering with treatment of serious animal illnesses. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> seized a large quantity of drugs July 9, 1986, from <ORGANIZATION> Schuyler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratories </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Rushville </LO