<HEAD>50 Detainees Freed; Hunger Strike Continues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government freed 50 detainees Tuesday after a hunger strike in two prisons was halted, but at least 226 detainees still are fasting elsewhere, police and lawyers said. Police said they have hospitalized 20 of the hunger strikers, who are demanding they be freed or put on trial. Many have been held without charge for more than two years. Law and Order Minister <PERSON> Adriaan </PERSON> <PERSON> Vlok </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> he signed release warrants for 50 detainees. He said the hunger strikes were orchestrated outside prisons by opposition groups seeking `` to discredit the South African government.'' `` Inside the prisons it is the work of a small group of ringleaders _ hardened leftist activists _ who by means of cruel intimidation control the group to such a degree that many detainees are too afraid to break away,'' <PERSON> Vlok </PERSON> said. Veteran anti-apartheid legislator <PERSON> Helen </PERSON> <PERSON> Suzman </PERSON> said detainees decided on their `` extremely dangerous course'' only after exhausting all avenues for airing their grievances. `` By what criteria does the minister -LRB- <PERSON> Vlok </PERSON> -RRB- decide that people must be kept away from the community?'' she asked. `` He should not be worried about saving face, he should be worried about saving lives.'' Hunger strikes continued in the southern cities of <LOCATION> Durban </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pietermaritzburg </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. Police said 20 hunger strikers in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> were hospitalized Monday, four days after they began fasting with six fellow detainees. Civil rights lawyers said at least 200 detainees in <LOCATION> Durban </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pietermaritzburg </LOCATION> have begun hunger strikes in the past two weeks. <PERSON> Vlok </PERSON> has agreed to meet lawyers for these detainees, but no date has been set. The first hunger strike started Jan. 23 and involved nearly 300 detainees held without charge in <LOCATION> Port </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Elizabeth </LOCATION> and at Diepkloof Prison outside <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION>. That strike was suspended last week when <PERSON> Vlok </PERSON> promised to review detainees' cases and release `` a substantial number.'' Eight detainees were freed Friday. <PERSON> Vlok </PERSON> has been commended, even by anti-government leaders, for agreeing to meet lawyers, parents and clergymen representing the hunger strikers. However, anti-apartheid leader Rev. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Chikane </PERSON> said Monday some detainees who recently quit their hunger strike could resume if they are dissatisfied by the number of releases in the next two weeks. Under the 32-month state of emergency, police can arrest anyone they believe might endanger public safety. <PERSON> Vlok </PERSON> decides periodically, based on reports from police officers, whether the detainee should remain incarcerated. Monitoring groups have said more than 30,000 people, mostly blacks, have been detained for some period of time during the emergency. <PERSON> Vlok </PERSON> has never given a total figure, but he said earlier this month there were fewer than 1,000 people in detention. On Tuesday, he said no youths under 16 were in detention. He said there were 22 detainees who were 16 years old and 30 who were 17.
