<HEAD>Crusading Brazilian Bishop Going Strong at 80</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER MUELLO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Archbishop <PERSON> Helder </PERSON> <PERSON> Camara </PERSON> has turned 80, an age at which many clergymen slip quietly into retirement. But the human rights crusader of the 1960s and 1970s remains an outspoken defender of the poor at the request of Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> II. `` Following the <PERSON> pope </PERSON>'s instructions, I will not hang up my spikes,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> leader said. In accordance with church rules, <LOCATION> Camara </LOCATION> _ known worldwide as <PERSON> Dom </PERSON> <PERSON> Helder </PERSON>, the Portuguese title for the high clergy _ had to retire at 75 as archbishop of <LOCATION> Recife </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Olinda </PERSON> on <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s northeast coast but maintained his title. `` I'm as busy now as I ever was,'' said the short, slight prelate, seeming even smaller in a voluminous khaki cassock adorned with a simple wooden cross. The interview came amid a heavy schedule of speeches and celebrations marking his 80th birthday Feb. 7. During a right-wing military regime in the world's largest <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> nation from 1964 to 1985, <PERSON> Camara </PERSON> denounced torture and human rights abuses in the face of death threats and a machine-gun attack on his parish house. The generals branded Camara the `` Red Bishop'' and banned his name from news broadcasts. His supporters nominated him for the Nobel Peace Prize. Those dark days have ended, but <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s chronic poverty persists with the collusion of powerful economic interests, he says. `` The forces behind these conditions are well-known. Large multinational corporations create great problems here,'' he said. `` The multinationals have very different attitudes in their own countries from those they have in ours.'' In 25 years as archbishop, <PERSON> Camara </PERSON> has condemned the `` exploitation'' of the Third World by the industrialized nations. He also has criticized Communist powers for imposing their will on smaller countries, but reserves his harshest words for his main cause these days, land reform. `` It's a scandal,'' he said. `` How can 20 percent of the people own 80 percent of the land in a country 34 times the size of <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>?'' Since 1980, more than 1,000 people _ mostly landless peasants _ have been killed in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> in rural property disputes. `` The church supports land reform, but it does n't intend to be political. No violence or radicalization,'' the archbishop said. Asked if he agreed with progressive clergymen who endorse land invasions by the homeless, <PERSON> Camara </PERSON> paused. `` This business of invasions is funny,'' he said. `` I laugh when these big landowners say, ` My land was invaded.' Where did they get it? Was n't that an invasion?'' <PERSON> Camara </PERSON> said the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> also is `` very well informed'' about the land reform issue. `` He thinks it's now possible to end this scandal,'' he said. Although the pope has emphatically told priests to stay out of politics and has punished radical Brazilian theologists, in 1980 he met in <LOCATION> Recife </LOCATION> with <PERSON> Camara </PERSON>, then considered a `` non-person'' by the military government. On live nationwide and international TV, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> embraced <PERSON> Dom </PERSON> <PERSON> Helder </PERSON> and said, `` This man is a friend of the poor. He is my friend.'' Camara remembered that with emotion. `` The pope is greater than many people think,'' he said. `` He is as great as <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> XXIII </PERSON>.'' That pontiff, who reigned from 1958-63, was widely known for his warm, human character. The archbishop said he is not discouraged by the immense social problems in this country of 144 million, where modern skyscrapers exist side-by-side with miserable shantytowns, and where the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> says the income distribution between the rich and the poor is the most unfair in the world. `` One thing I learned from young people: When the problems are absurd, the solutions become a passion,'' he said.
