<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Playwright <PERSON> Vaclav </PERSON> <PERSON> Havel </PERSON>, whose works are performed to acclaim abroad but banned in his homeland, has become a symbol of resistance to <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>'s Communist authorities. On Tuesday, <PERSON> Havel </PERSON> was convicted of participating in a banned rally and sentenced to nine months in prison. It was the latest government move against the country's best-known dissident since the 1950s. Books with the lined face of the blond, mustachioed writer are not found in Czechoslovak libraries or bookshops, but <PERSON> Havel </PERSON>'s outspoken human rights statements have brought him admiration beyond his works `` What is encouraging is that the young people know him,'' his brother <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> said in an interview this week at the <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> flat the two share with their wives. `` This is paradoxical _ whatever happens bad to him, whatever happens good to him, everything only increases his popularity.'' When the 52-year-old <PERSON> Havel </PERSON> was invited on stage at a folk music festival in September, 5,000 people cheered. When the authorities surprisingly allowed an independent demonstration in <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> on Dec. 10, crowds chanted `` Long Live Havel!'' before he could speak. About 100 sympathizers gave the same chant Tuesday when <PERSON> Havel </PERSON> was led to court, and more than 2,000 Czechoslovak intellectuals, including <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> members, had signed petitions for <PERSON> Havel </PERSON>'s release Born Oct. 5, 1936, the son of a civil engineer who built several famous <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> landmarks, he first encountered difficulties with authorities in the 1950s, when his bourgeois background barred him from university studies. Between 1963 and 1968, in a flowering of Czechoslovak culture that produced many well-known films and writers, <PERSON> Havel </PERSON> had three plays performed in <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION>. But after the Soviet-led invasion of 1968, <PERSON> Havel </PERSON> was among dozens of writers whose works were banned in their homeland. A critical open letter to communist leader <PERSON> Gustav </PERSON> <PERSON> Husak </PERSON> in 1975 and his part in founding the Charter 77 human rights movement in 1977 led to almost constant harassment and detention. In the letter to <PERSON> Husak </PERSON>, <PERSON> Havel </PERSON> accused the Communist authorities of creating `` a bureaucratic order of gray monotony that stifles all individuality.'' `` True enough, the country is calm,'' <PERSON> Havel </PERSON> wrote then. `` Calm as a morgue or as a grave, would n't you say?'' In 1979, when <PERSON> Havel </PERSON> was convicted for sedition and sentenced to four years in prison, nobody in <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> spoke up for him. But he already was well-known in the West, where he received numerous awards and his plays drew critical praise. In giving <PERSON> Havel </PERSON> the Erasmus Prize in 1986, the Rotterdam-based <ORGANIZATION> Erasmus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> said he was driven `` by the search for truth in its purest form'' and lauded his ability to be critical of societies in both East and West. <PERSON> Havel </PERSON> has refused many invitations to go to the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>, fearing that would mean leaving behind his native <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> and his wife of 24 years, <PERSON> Olga </PERSON>. Last year, a book of his letters from prison to <PERSON> Olga </PERSON> <PERSON> Havel </PERSON> was published in the West. He would like to travel in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, he Told the <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> in an interview last year. `` But I do n't think they will give me a passport,'' he added with a smile.
