<HEAD>Flag Maker Defends Label-switching Proposal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The company that suggested <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> importers of its <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> flags switch the `` Made in <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'' label to `` Made in <LOCATION> USA </LOCATION>'' said it wants nothing more to do with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> protectionism. General Manager <PERSON> Ni </PERSON> <PERSON> Feng-ming </PERSON> said his company has switched to making national flags for <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> after the 1987 suggestion to switch labels failed to get many <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> orders. `` We stopped sales to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> about two years ago because our products were strongly rejected,'' Ni Feng-ming, general manager of <PERSON> Ming </PERSON> <PERSON> Teh </PERSON>, said in an interview. `` I guess Americans hate to see their national flag made by foreigners.'' The businessman added: `` American protectionism is really scary.'' Although <PERSON> Ni </PERSON> says his company no longer exports <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> flags to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> because of protectionism and the appreciation of the <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> dolla, both <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> officials have expressed concern over Ming Teh's label-switching suggestion. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> has ordered closer scrutiny of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> flags from <PERSON> Ming </PERSON> <PERSON> Teh </PERSON> following complaints from American flag manufacturers and several members of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. An official at <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday authorities have started an investigation to determine whether <PERSON> Ming </PERSON> <PERSON> Teh </PERSON> violated any law. The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said <LOCATION> Taipei </LOCATION> would take measures to `` discourage any label-switching ideas.'' Ni stressed his company never changed the labels on its flags. He said a salesperson suggested in June 1987 promotional letters that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> importers remove `` Made in <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'' tags from the company's half-finished exports and add a `` Made In <LOCATION> USA </LOCATION>'' label once processing was completed in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> <PERSON> Ming </PERSON> <PERSON> Teh </PERSON> dyed and printed the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> flags and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies did cutting and sewing, according to Ni. The huge <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> trade surplus with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has led to friction between the two countries. Last year, the surplus was $ 10.4 billion on total trade of $ 36.43 billion. <PERSON> Mou </PERSON> <PERSON> Tun </PERSON>, an official at the <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> External </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Ming </PERSON> <PERSON> Teh </PERSON> was just `` trying to be considerate'' by offering an alternative to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> importers who wanted to buy Taiwan-made flags but did not want to upset <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> flag makers.
