<HEAD>Eds: Subs 9 grafs with Michigan case for last graf pvs</HEAD>
<HEAD>Court Will Take Up `Exclusionary Rule' Case from Illinois</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday it will consider relaxing significantly the so-called `` exclusionary rule'' that bars from criminal trials any evidence police seized unlawfully. The court said it will use a case from <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> to decide whether statements made by a criminal defendant after an unlawful arrest may be used by prosecutors to contradict a defense witness' trial testimony. The court previously has allowed prosecutors to use unlawfully seized evidence to contradict a defendant's own trial testimony. But the justices never before have allowed the use of such evidence to rebut other witnesses' testimony. The <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, by a 4-3 vote, allowed such evidence to be introduced at the trial of <PERSON> Darryl </PERSON> <PERSON> James </PERSON>, sentenced to 30 years in prison for a 1982 murder. <PERSON> James </PERSON> was 15 when arrested in his mother's beauty parlor for two Aug. 30, 1982, shootings. He was tried as an adult. Prosecutors said <PERSON> James </PERSON> shot and killed <PERSON> Geliria </PERSON> <PERSON> Boyd </PERSON> and wounded another youth in a late-night confrontation on a south <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> street. Several prosecution witnesses identified <PERSON> James </PERSON> as the triggerman, and testified that on the night of the crime he had long, reddish-brown hair. At his trial, <PERSON> James </PERSON> had short, black hair. <PERSON> James </PERSON> did not testify at his trial but two defense witnesses testified in his behalf. One said that <PERSON> James </PERSON> had short, black hair the night of the shootings. Prosecutors then won court permission to let a police detective testify that <PERSON> James </PERSON>, when arrested, said he had long, reddish-brown hair the night of the crime. The trial judge previously had ruled that <PERSON> James </PERSON>' arrest was unlawful because police at the time did not have a court warrant or probable cause to suspect him of committing a crime. As a result, the police detective was not allowed to testify directly about what <PERSON> James </PERSON> had told him the night of the arrest. But the detective was allowed to testify about <PERSON> James </PERSON>' remarks to rebut the defense witness' testimony. In a related case from <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, the court said it will decide whether evidence obtained unlawfully after a defendant has been arraigned can ever be used in court. A <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> appeals court said no, and threw out <PERSON> Tyris </PERSON> <PERSON> Lemont </PERSON> <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON>'s 1986 conviction in <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> on charges of criminal sexual conduct. He had been sentenced to six to 10 years in prison. The state court said <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> was entitled to a new trial because a police officer should not have been allowed to testify about comments <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> made during an unlawful police interrogation six days before his trial. The testimony was not offered as part of the prosecution's case but only to rebut some of <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON>'s trial testimony. The state court acknowledged that evidence obtained in violation of a defendant's Fourth or Fifth Amendment rights _ to be free from unreasonable police searches and the privilege against self-incrimination _ sometimes may be used to rebut or impeach a defendant's testimony. But it ruled that the statement made to the police officer violated <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON>'s Sixth Amendment right to effective legal help. `` A statement so acquired may not be used for any purpose, including impeachment,'' the state court ruled. The ruling was appealed by <LOCATION> Wayne </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> prosecutors. The cases are <PERSON> James </PERSON> vs. <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, 88-6075, and <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> vs. <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON>, 88-512.
</TEXT>
