<HEAD>Homesick Boat People Volunteering to Return to Vietnam</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BIERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Seven months after a risky escape by boat from <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> said Tuesday he is ready to take another risk and return to his communist homeland. `` I miss my parents and family,'' the 29-year-old told reporters who visited the <ORGANIZATION> Argyle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Street </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Holding </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> where he and 79 other Vietnamese are awaiting repatriation. They are expected to return to <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> next month and will be the first group of boat people to go home voluntarily from this British colony, which has more than 25,000 Vietnamese languishing in camps. <PERSON> Deng </PERSON>, speaking through an interpreter, said he was afraid of being imprisoned in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> but would go back anyway because he was homesick for his family. He decided he wanted to go home a month after his July 17 arrival in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>. Other Vietnamese who plan to go back also mentioned their families left behind. <PERSON> Dien </PERSON> <PERSON> Tan </PERSON> <PERSON> Sang </PERSON>, 30, who fled to <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> with his wife and three children, said he decided to return `` because my parents are in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> and there is nobody to take care of them.'' <PERSON> Dien </PERSON>, who spoke as his 4-year-old son sat weeping in his lap, said he did not know whether he would be punished when they returned. Asked if he were frightened, he slowly shook his head and said: `` I am not afraid.'' Both men said they were from the Vietnamese town of <PERSON> Quang </PERSON> <PERSON> Ninh </PERSON> and that they fled to <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, about 500 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, because others had done so. The trips typically are made in overcrowded and rickety craft. Reporters previously had not been allowed to speak with the boat people who have agreed to return home. Only 22 boat people voluntarily returned to <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> between 1979, when nearly 70,000 arrived, and 1988. But a tough new <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> policy that no longer accepts all boat people as eligible for resettlement appears to have convinced some Vietnamese to return home. The Argyle Center group was issued travel documents by an official <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION> delegation that visited the colony this month. They were among the more than 10,000 boat people who have arrived since the <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> government introduced a policy in June under which Vietnamese face forced repatriation unless they can prove they fled their homeland because of persecution. Most boat people who have arrived since the new policy took effect wo n't be granted refugee status, and those who are eligible for resettlement might have to wait years before they are accepted by another country. <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> officials have said they hope smooth repatriation of the first group will lead other boat people to volunteer to go home. <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> signed an agreement late last year on the voluntary return of boat people. Under it, <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION> agreed to treat returnees well and the international organization is to provide them with assistance.
