<TEXT>
 Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> joined rescuers and survivors of last month's British <LOCATION> Midland </LOCATION> air crash at a memorial service Tuesday for the 47 people who died. Before a gathering of 1,300 people at <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Anne </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Anglican </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cathedral </LOCATION>, leaders of <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>'s four main churches unveiled a scroll for permanent display listing the names of those who died when the Belfast-bound <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737 crashed in central <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> on Jan. 8. British <ORGANIZATION> Midland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Bishop </PERSON> read a passage from the Bible and Archbishop <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Eames </PERSON>, primate of the <LOCATION> Anglican </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Church </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>, talked of the responsibility borne by those who provide public transport. `` It is at times like this that we are made aware of the awesome responsibility of those who provide public transportation, of those who for a few hours hold so many human lives in their hands,'' <PERSON> Eames </PERSON> said. But he praised the airline, saying: `` From the chairman to the youngest stewardess their reaction and their humanity went far beyond the call of duty.'' The jet crashed into the side of a major highway, close to the runway of <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Midlands </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>, after reporting engine trouble. The cause is under investigation. Among the congregation were some of the 79 survivors of the crash, some in wheelchairs or on crutches, and relatives of those who died. Twenty-six of the victims were from <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>. Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> flew to <LOCAT