<HEAD>GAO Says Agency Officials Ordered Changes in Report on Spotted Owl</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Fish and <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> officials, in an effort to keep the spotted owl off the endangered list, ordered changes in a report which originally said the bird may face extinction, according to a <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> report released Tuesday. The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION>, an arm of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, said officials ignored scientific evidence and ordered revisions in a study prepared by biologists in the agency's Northwest regional office. Scientists had concluded that unless logging was slowed in ancient forests of the <LOCATION> Northwest </LOCATION>, the owl could face extinction. The timber industry in the <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> has opposed any effort to name the owl a threatened or endangered species, fearing that such a move would disrupt logging in public forests. Environmentalists have advocated protecting the owl as part of their campaign to halt logging of old growth forests. `` While changes are an inevitable part of any draft report review process, the nature of the changes made in this case and the way they were made raise questions about whether objectivity was maintained,'' the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said. The Fish and <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, an <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> agency which determines what should be designated for protection as threatened or endangered, is required to consider only `` biological factors'' in making its decision. The service concluded in December 1987 that the owl, which lives only in old growth forests of <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and northern <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, was not endangered, and refused to grant a petition requesting that the bird be protected. The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said decisions on whether to classify a bird, animal or plant as endangered `` can often be surrounded by highly emotional debates centered on the decision's possible economic consequences rather than its biological merits. `` In such cases especially, the Fish and <ORGANIZATION> Wildife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> needs to be able to demonstrate that its review process and ultimate decisions have been thorough, independent, and objective as possible,'' <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said. `` There is evidence the spotted owl process did not meet such standards.'' The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said agency `` management officials substantially changed the body of scientific evidence'' found in the original report. `` The revisions had the effect of changing the report from one that emphasized the dangers facing the owl to one that could more easily support denying the listing petition,'' the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said. The agency's decision not to list the owl as endangered was challenged in court and a federal judge has given the service until May 1 to provide additional information on how it reached its decision. An agency spokesman on Tuesday declined comment on the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> report. `` We would like to at least read it first,'' said <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Reiben </PERSON>, a Fish and <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> spokesman. `` The Fish and <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>'s decision not to list the spotted owl as an endangered species appears to have been based on politics, not science or law,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Gerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Studds </PERSON>, D-Mass. He said he planned to ask Fish and <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> Director <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunkle </PERSON> about the case at a hearing Wednesday. Rep. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> DeFazio </PERSON>, D-Ore., said the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> report shows the decision not to protect the owl was a `` simple case of political expediency winning out over sound scientific evaluation and good policy `` We need the scientific facts about the spotted owl, not the biased views of political appointees at the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION>.''
