<HEAD>California Town Sets Up Computer Link between Residents and Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Computer-equipped citizens can fire off an angry electronic letter to <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hall </ORGANIZATION>, see if their favorite book is at the library or check the bus schedule in a pioneering program switched on Tuesday. Experts say <PERSON> Santa </PERSON> <PERSON> Monica </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electronic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION> is at the leading edge of a national trend linking local governments to their constituents through computers. This affluent coastal <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> suburb began enrolling computer owners in the service Tuesday, and City Manager <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Jalili </PERSON> said interest appeared high, though a customer count for the free service was n't immediately available. Once a citizen has been enrolled and assigned a password to get into the system, he or she will be able to tap into city files on proposed developments and other <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> action, find out how to get city permits and licenses, get schedules for city services and get a range of consumer advice. They'll also be able to sound off, directing `` electronic mail'' at council members, department heads and the public at large. The city promises to respond. `` I love it,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Hill </PERSON>, a teacher and active citizen who was the first to sign up for PEN. `` We live in an electronic age and we have this technology that allows us to use computers to access information.'' He planned to fire up his home computer Tuesday afternoon to offer some ideas on how to fit a park improvement project into the new budget. `` Then I'll probably e-mail -LRB- electronic mail -RRB- the information services department head and congratulate him on a job well done,'' <PERSON> Hill </PERSON> said. The system is housed in a computer separate from the city's internal data processing to head off the threat of `` hackers'' seeking inside information or planting destructive viruses Although <PERSON> Santa </PERSON> <PERSON> Monica </PERSON>'s system appears to go further than most, many local governments around the country are experimenting with computer citizen communications, said <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Shogry </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, group that researches technology for local governemnts. <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Hillsborough </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, have `` 24-hour City Halls,'' which allow citizens to browse through reams of information using computer kiosks set up in public places, he said. The organization is planning a 12-city test later this year of a `` videotext'' information system linking citizens with their governments. The cities have yet to be chosen. <LOCATION> Charlotte </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, have `` voice mail'' systems for callers to get recorded information on a variety of services and problems, he said. `` It's attracting a lot of interest by local governments across the country,'' <PERSON> Shogry </PERSON> said. `` There's a growing awareness of how telecommunications and computer technology can be used to involve more people.'' <PERSON> Santa </PERSON> <PERSON> Monica </PERSON>'s <PERSON> Jalili </PERSON> sees the system as a way to improve service to citizens. `` First of all, it's going to stop the phone game where people are transferred to eight different places,'' <PERSON> Jalili </PERSON> said. `` And there are people who during their work day ca n't call in and when they get home City Hall is closed.'' Of course, many people who need help or information from City Hall do n't have personal computers. In <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Monica </LOCATION>, known for the liberal politics of such celebrity residents as actress <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Fonda </PERSON>, project organizers are sensitive to the perception they're bypassing the poor. Terminals have been installed in all libraries and there are plans to put them in recreation buildings and in a senior citizens' center under construction Elsewhere, the equipment put in public places is designed for easy use by those who are n't familiar with computers: Some have touch-sensitive screens to make typing unnecessary, and all have simple instructions to lead users throught the microchip maze. `` My personal opinion is that for the electronic democracy to become a reality, the needs of the poor or less educated will have to be kind of aggressively addressed,'' <PERSON> Shogry </PERSON> said. In the case of <ORGANIZATION> Santa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monica </ORGANIZATION>, a survey found 33 percent of residents owned personal computers and 23 percent had modems, the devices needed to allow the computers to communicate over telephone lines. For now, the experiment is free to the city and to subscribers. The $ 350,000 system was a gift from two computer companies _ <ORGANIZATION> Hewlett </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Packard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> donated the machines and <ORGANIZATION> Metasystems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> provided the software. But fees are n't ruled out in the future, said <PERSON> Jalili </PERSON>, depending on how much staff time is involved.
