<SECOND>AM-Gorbachev,0622</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet President Defends Policy on Cooperatives</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> on Tuesday defended a government order freezing cooperatives out of the medical business, saying the private business was taking up too many government resources. His remarks, broadcast on the evening TV news program `` Vremya,'' came on a visit to <LOCATION> Lvov </LOCATION> on his trip to the Ukrainian republic. The 57-year-old Soviet leader toured a television factory, addressed city scientific and cultural leaders, and held discussions with groups of citizens at the airport and on street corners. The official Soviet media said <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> will visit the <LOCATION> Chernobyl </LOCATION> area on his trip, nearly three years after the world's worst nuclear power plant disaster occurred there. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said in response to a complaint from an elderly woman about medical cooperatives that <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> officials heard some medical equipment was not being used in the state-run system so it would be ready for cooperatives, which charge their patients. `` After 2 or 3 o'clock, everything worked fine,'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said. `` It turned out that in the first part of the day it was being prepared to be used for cooperatives.'' In late December the government ordered cooperatives out of the medical field, TV stores and other potentially high-profit services that also require relatively big investments. Government officials said they moved against medical cooperatives to ensure public health. But leaders of the cooperative movement saw it as an effort to keep them out of profitable areas. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has pushed the cooperative movement as a means to provide goods and services that the state-run economy can not or will not provide. He said the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> needs them but should control them through taxation and efforts to limit the amount of money their workers can earn. <LOCATION> Lvov </LOCATION>, a railway, automobile assembly and oil refining city with a population of 753,000, lies 260 miles west of <LOCATION> Kiev </LOCATION>, in a part of the <LOCATION> Ukraine </LOCATION> that became part of the Soviet Union only at the end of World War II. <LOCATION> Lvov </LOCATION> is still a center of Ukrainian nationalism. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> toured the Elektron factory, and factory workers told him about plans to increase output of TV sets, which <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said were in short supply. Aside from being scarce, Soviet television sets are notoriously dangerous. The state-run press has carried articles saying Soviet-made color TV sets are prone to explode and are a major cause of fires. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> found out Monday in <LOCATION> Kiev </LOCATION>, the republic's capital, that the dangers of nuclear power are still much on the minds of Ukrainians. In a street encounter broadcast on television, an elderly woman asked <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> why another nuclear power plant was being built in the <LOCATION> Crimea </LOCATION>. The area contains some of the country's most popular beach resorts and is home to 2 million people. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said he was aware of worries about plant safety. He said American specialists had been asked to study the Crimean facility. `` Construction is under way,'' he said. `` But if the conclusion -LRB- of the specialists -RRB- is that it is not advisable to build a station there, then it will be turned into a training center for personnel, not an atomic power station.'' An explosion and fire at a nuclear reactor at <LOCATION> Chernobyl </LOCATION> on April 26, 1986, killed at least 31 people and sent a radioactive cloud around the world. Since then, the Soviets have moved away from complete faith in the safety of nuclear power, and public opposition to it has grown. Last week, <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> said cancer cases have doubled in a region 30 miles from <LOCATION> Chernobyl </LOCATION> where people were not evacuated.
