<HEAD>Senators Say Congress Will Review Secrets Law After North Trial</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-North Trial Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Democratic leaders said Tuesday that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> will review a law governing the use of national security secrets in criminal cases because of the legal tangle created by the trial of <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Maine </LOCATION>, said the use of an independent counsel to prosecute North on charges of lying to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> about the Iran-Contra affair had not been anticipated in the law covering how to handle secret evidence. `` In this case, the balance which the law assumed would be there does not exist,'' <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> told reporters. `` It is obvious that the prior administration and this administration is not eagerly seeking ... prosecution. Indeed, its political interest lies in no trial at all.'' To help ensure that the administration did not forfeit the <PERSON> North </PERSON> case for political reasons, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> held a closed-door session to hear from <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> Director <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> on the administration's reasons for dropping conspiracy charges against <PERSON> North </PERSON> in January. North's trial on 12 other charges began Tuesday. `` We heard from members of the intelligence community who shared their national security concerns about information that could be developed during the course of the trial now under way,'' said Sen. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Boren </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Okla </LOCATION>., chairman of the intelligence panel <PERSON> Boren </PERSON> declined to say whether he was satisfied that those concerns were legitimate or to characterize <PERSON> Webster </PERSON>'s level of worry about the classified information, saying he did not want to open himself to charges of influencing the case. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> passed the Classified Information Procedures Act in 1980, propelled by a spate of cases in which defendants threatened to disclose government secrets as part of their defense against criminal charges. The law defines national security secrets and allows a trial judge to screen such information before a trial to determine whether the material can be used in open court. The judge can dismiss a case or specific counts of an indictment if the government objects to disclosure of classified information. The same law requires the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to report to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on cases not prosecuted or charges dropped because of fears of disclosure of secrets. `` We will carefully review -LRB- the law -RRB- when this is over to see if changes are necessary,'' <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> said. `` We are dealing with situations here which might not have been anticipated by the law when it was written,'' added <PERSON> Boren </PERSON>. `` It would be appropriate for us to reflect upon when all is said and done'' in the North case.
