<HEAD>Government to Change Inscription on Katyn Monument</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government said Tuesday it will change a monument inscription saying the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> killed more than 4,000 Polish army officers during World War II. It cited a <ORGANIZATION> Polish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> document that indicates the Soviets killed them. The announcement came from government spokesman <PERSON> Jerzy </PERSON> <PERSON> Urban </PERSON>, who stopped short of saying that the Soviets were guilty of the crime in the <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Forest </LOCATION> in western <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION>. He also did not say what the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> monument will read. `` We expect that this problem will be explained by the two sides and on the basis of more comprehensive information,'' Urban told a news conference. Urban referred to a broadcast by <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION> on Monday which, according to Urban, said the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> report was `` serious evidence requiring serious examination that the <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION> crime was committed by Soviet security forces in the Stalinist epoch, and not by the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION>.'' The 12-foot granite monument at <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>'s Powazki Cemetery has an inscription at its base saying it is `` To Polish Soldiers _ Victims of Hitlerite Fascism Resting in the Ground of <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION>.'' Urban said the government also plans to move the monument, now in an out-of-the-way corner of the cemetery. The massacre in the <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Forest </LOCATION>, 12 miles west of <LOCATION> Smolensk </LOCATION>, is one of the most searing issues in <LOCATION> Polish-Soviet </LOCATION> relations, and for years the word itself was too sensitive to be uttered in public. Official postwar histories all maintained the officers were killed by <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> in winter 1941, but most Poles and Western historians have said they were killed by the Soviets in the spring of 1940, when the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> were still allied. In addition to the 4,300 bodies found at <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION>, 11,000 other officers are unaccounted for and presumed dead after they were imprisoned in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in the first days of World War II. The officers represented about half of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s prewar officer corps. The monument blaming the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> for <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION> was erected in April 1985 and unveiled without public notice after some family members of <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION> victims erected unauthorized crosses at the site in memory of the slain officers. The crosses were taken down. Each Aug. 1 and Nov. 1, dates when Poles remember their war dead, large groups of people gather at the monument, and many use candles and flowers to cover over the inscription they regard as false. A joint committee of Polish and Soviet historians created in April 1987 is examining the <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION> issue as part of an effort to correct `` blank spots'' in the two countries' history. In November, the Soviet newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION> reported that the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministers </ORGANIZATION> approved plans for a monument in <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION> for prisoners of war, but the report gave no construction schedule.
