<HEAD>World Record Holder Dies in Parachute Jump</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SHERIDAN, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Frenchman fell to his death doing what he had done more than anyone else in the world _ parachute jumping. `` He would jump with anybody anytime,'' said <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Mayfield </PERSON>, founder of the <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parachute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, where 59-year-old <PERSON> Roch </PERSON> <PERSON> Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> Charmet </PERSON> died Monday when his parachute failed to open properly. `` That was his whole life.'' Charmet, who held the world record for the most parachute jumps with more than 14,000, had made six jumps when he went up for what was to be the last for the day. <PERSON> Mayfield </PERSON> on Tuesday recalled that on the way up <PERSON> Charmet </PERSON> played a <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> drinking song, something about knights of the Round Table drinking wine, on a harmonica he recently learned to play. Charmet jumped out at 2,500 feet. `` Normally, you wait three or four seconds and pull out a hand-deployed pilot chute,'' said <PERSON> Mayfield </PERSON>. `` I could see him fighting with something. At 500 feet the pilot chute came out, then just a ball of material is all we could see.'' He pulled the release on his back-up parachute, but it was too late, <PERSON> Mayfield </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Charmet </PERSON> landed on a stack of lumber. An investigator from the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> arrived Tuesday to inspect the parachute gear, which <PERSON> Charmet </PERSON> had packed himself. <PERSON> Charmet </PERSON> lived in <LOCATION> Montlhery </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, and was an instructor with the <ORGANIZATION> Parachute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> France </ORGANIZATION>, authorities said. Small and lightly built with a gray beard and long gray hair, he learned to jump while serving with the French Foreign Legion in <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION> in the 1950s, and his 14,600-odd parachute jumps were recognized as the world record by the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> States </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parachute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Mayfield </PERSON> said. `` His favorite saying was, ` Only skydivers know why birds sing,''' <PERSON> Mayfield </PERSON> said. `` It's the freedom he would feel of leaving the aircraft and being able to fly. That's what he felt.'' For the past 15 years, <PERSON> Charmet </PERSON> had been spending a few months each winter in this town of 2,400 people situated about 45 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>. `` He originally came here because he fell in love with a girl traveling in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> who was from here,'' <PERSON> Mayfield </PERSON> said. `` He followed her here. When he arrived she was married to somebody else. He liked the area and the people here, so he just came back every year.'' While in <LOCATION> Sheridan </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Charmet </PERSON> jumped repeatedly and broke the world record here last year. <PERSON> Charmet </PERSON>'s passion was accuracy jumping, leaving an airplane at 2,500 feet and landing on a 5-centimeter target. `` He'd make like 800 jumps in three months,'' <PERSON> Mayfield </PERSON> said. `` He would line up four or five parachutes, pack them all, then make four or five jumps. He would do this all day long.''
