<HEAD>Additional $30 Million Damages Recommended in 1978 Oil Spill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A retired judge Tuesday recommended a $ 30 million increase in his $ 85.2 million judgment against <ORGANIZATION> Amoco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> for oil-spill damage from the 1978 wreck of a supertanker off the French coast. The revised award would be shared by the government of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> _ which would receive the single largest portion, $ 44.4 million _ and some 100 French towns affected by the spill that fouled 100 miles of coastline. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> McGarr </PERSON>, who retired as a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> judge after his 1988 ruling, continues to serve as special master in the case and made the recommendation after being asked by parties in the case to reconsider the award. The recommendation is subject to approval by another federal judge; no date has been set for a final judgment. Both sides objected to the revised award as well and vowed to appeal. None of the money has been paid. The towns had received $ 7.3 million in the original judgment and sought an additional $ 8 million but received only $ 200,000 more. `` Today's damage determinations continue to support the position the <ORGANIZATION> Amoco </ORGANIZATION> parties have maintained throughout: that the claims of damage from this unfortunate incident were exaggerated,'' Chicago-based <ORGANIZATION> Amoco </ORGANIZATION> said in a statement. `` What we will be asking the appeals court to do is recognize the damage to the environment, the livelihoods of the people in <LOCATION> Brittany </LOCATION>, and the quality of life,'' said attorney <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Kingham </PERSON>, who represented the towns, association of oystermen and fishermen, hoteliers, and the two French counties most affected by the spill. `` The judge refused to recognize those damages and he continues to reject them. He simply gave out-of-pocket expenses for the cleanup effort.'' Attorneys for both sides said the revised award totals about $ 115 million _ $ 61 million in damages and between $ 54 million and $ 60 million in interest. The supertanker <ORGANIZATION> Amoco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cadiz </ORGANIZATION> ran aground two miles off the Brittany coast. The tanker, which had lost the use of its rudder, had been under tow through the English Channel when the towlines snapped in hurricane-force winds and heavy seas. The tanker lost 68 million gallons of mostly Iranian light crude oil valued at $ 24 million. The spill killed thousands of birds and millions of sea creatures and washing wave after wave of thick black tar along the coast. In 1984, <PERSON> McGarr </PERSON> ruled that <ORGANIZATION> Amoco </ORGANIZATION> and two subsidiaries were liable because of negligence in the design, repair and maintenance of the vessel, which was 300 feet wide and longer than three football fields.
