<HEAD>Communist Leadership Asking Whether 1950s Political Trials Were Rigged</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Communist leaders have asked historians and jurists to determine whether political trials in the 1950s were rigged, an official said Tuesday. The move could be a step toward rehabilitating leaders of the 1956 anti-communist uprising, some of whom were executed and buried in unmarked graves. The Communist party leadership, on the second and final day of a <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> meeting, also heard a report on the new constitution, which is to leave out any reference to the leading role of the party and allow a multi-party system. <PERSON> Gyoergy </PERSON> <PERSON> Fejti </PERSON>, secretary of the party <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said the party has asked that a panel of legal experts and historians look into the period from 1946 to 1962 to `` expose any possibility of rigged procedures'' at trials conducted during that period. `` In search of a public consensus, we must strive to see that suitable amends are made to those affected within the rehabilitation process,'' <PERSON> Fejti </PERSON> told a news conference at the close of the meeting. But he appealed for patience and understanding, saying the historical review would `` take time and we do n't know what the results will be.'' The announcement came less than 10 days after the 108-member <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> partially reassessed the 1956 revolt. That meeting was provoked by leading reformer <PERSON> Imre </PERSON> <PERSON> Pozsgay </PERSON>, who said the revolt that for 32 years was termed a counterrevolution was a popular uprising. The leadership of the ruling <ORGANIZATION> Hungarian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION>' -LRB- communist -RRB- Party reached a compromise formulation saying the revolt had both popular and counterrevolutionary elements The revolt, led by <PERSON> Imre </