cleaned up. Some locations may be irreversibly contaminated,'' <PERSON> Peach </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Peach </PERSON> said the master plan calls for spending $ 401 million in the coming budget year on environmental cleanup that eventually will cost up to $ 70 billion. Several members of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> panel, including <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Spratt </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-S.C. </LOCATION>, also criticized the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, saying it has put more emphasis on nuclear materials production than on safe and environmentally sound operations. <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Berube </PERSON>, the department's deputy assistant secretary for environment, said, `` There is no current immediate public health and safety risk'' posed by the weapons plants. He said there would be a threat if the environmental issues were put off. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON>, meanwhile, said the department still expected to restart at least one of its tritium-producing reactors, at the <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plant </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, by the end of the year. He said a firm timetable would be available next month.
