 the same as other types of semiautomatic rifles. The only real difference, he said, is that the military-style weapons have certain `` external additions'' like bolts on the barrels or attaching bayonets. <PERSON> Gardiner </PERSON> preferred to use the term `` self-loading'' rather than semiautomatic and asserted that semiautomatic weapons that have come into question are not assault rifles. He said only the fully automatic military versions of those guns, which fire repeatedly rather than once with each trigger pull, are assault rifles. `` The whole thing is largely a media creation and needs to be treated as such,'' <PERSON> Gardiner </PERSON> said.
