tnesses from the <ORGANIZATION> BIA </ORGANIZATION> said that despite a new policy requiring school personnel to report cases of sex abuse, the <ORGANIZATION> BIA </ORGANIZATION> does not get much information. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Mehojah </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> BIA </ORGANIZATION> branch chief for Indian elementary and secondary school programs, said no disciplinary action has ever been taken for failure to report. <PERSON> Mehojah </PERSON> and the others advocated enactment of a federal law similar to those in the states, making failure to report alleged sex abuse a crime. The opinion was echoed by two <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agents who investigate crime on Indian reservations in <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Dakotas </LOCATION>, and law enforcement officials working for the <ORGANIZATION> BIA </ORGANIZATION> and local authorities. <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agent <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Small </PERSON> said interviews with pedophiles have indicated that child molesters gravitate to Indian reservations because there is little supervision and they usually are in remote areas, making it easy to prey on children. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Haley </PERSON>, general chairman of the Indian law enforcement section of the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chiefs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION>, said investigation of child abuse cases are sometimes hampered by tribes which refuse to let the children off the reservation to testify. <PERSON> Mehojah </PERSON> said many teachers have gone to work before background checks were complete because of paperwork delays.
