<TEXT>
 Police blocked about 80 students marching to <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday with a petition calling for free elections. An opposition activist said at least 15 people were detained. Four more people were detained in <LOCATION> Krakow </LOCATION> at a demonstration in support of Czechoslovak playwright <PERSON> Vaclav </PERSON> <PERSON> Havel </PERSON>, who was sentenced in <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> on Tuesday to nine months in prison on charges stemming from a Jan. 16 protest there. Two banned political groups, the leftist <ORGANIZATION> Polish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and the rightist Confederation for an Independent <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, organized the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> demonstration. It began with a rally at <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> about 200 young people, who signed the petition calling for free elections and legalization of their groups. Then 80 to 100 of them began walking toward the Sejm, or parliament, about one mile away. Police blocked the students after they walked a short distance to a major intersection and wrestled some of them into police vans. <PERSON> Leszek </PERSON> <PERSON> Moczulski </PERSON>, leader of the Confederation, said at least 15 people were detained and three were still held by evening. <PERSON> Moczulski </PERSON> said police beat one Confederation activist, <PERSON> Slawomir </PERSON> <PERSON> Gasior </PERSON>, as he was being detained. The Confederation also organized a rally in <LOCATION> Krakow </LOCATION>'s market square, where about 1,000 people gathered to hear speeches supporting <PERSON> Havel </PERSON>, said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Bogdanski </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Solidarity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. He said police qui