<DATELINE>BAL HARBOUR, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The president of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Teachers </ORGANIZATION> says that unions have n't been quick enough in keeping up with changes in the workforce. And <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Shanker </PERSON> espouses unorthodox methods of restoring the stature of unions in the workplace, including the schools where his members teach. Among his proposed changes in the education system are abolishing the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> and placing its duties in the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, firing incompetent teachers and transforming high schools into campuslike environments where students have some flexibility in choosing classes. `` In this country we go on the pendulum swing system,'' <PERSON> Shanker </PERSON> said Tuesday during a breakfast meeting with reporters covering the <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION> Executive Council meeting here. `` First we had tough schools with rigorous standards where most kids are pushed out. Then we move to soft schools where everybody graduates but very few learn anything. `` Now we go back to the other way,'' <PERSON> Shanker </PERSON> said. `` It's pretty clear that if you have two ways of doing things and neither is working it's time to find a third way.'' That third way, in <PERSON> Shanker </PERSON>'s view, might include ideas unions have traditionally opposed, including the use of part-time teachers. A shortage of qualified math and science teachers has made the use of part-timers a viable approach that labor should support although those teachers are unlikely to join the union, <PERSON> Shanker </PERSON> said. `` We have to encourage non-traditional methods,'' said <PERSON> Shanker </PERSON>, who has been president of the 690,000-member AFT since 1974. He carries that approach over to overall union organizing, a once-militant union leader calling on his colleagues to relax the standards he says are partly to blame for the declining share of unionized workers in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` Unions themselves have not adequately recongnized the changing of the labor force,'' <PERSON> Shanker </PERSON> said. `` It's the failure in many cases to switch the nature of your appeal fast enough.'' As the demographics of the workforce change to include fewer workers in high-risk factory jobs and more in white-collar professions, unions must change equally fast to appeal to professionals, <PERSON> Shanker </PERSON> said. Included in those changes, he said, should be new membership categories such as associate memberships that would offer workers who are not members of a collective bargaining unit some union services. That concept is the subject of a heated internal debate that delayed the scheduled release this week of a major report on labor organizing. Hard-liners object to the concept of associate memberships on grounds that labor is conceding too much in its drive to fill up membership rolls. <PERSON> Shanker </PERSON> will get a chance to discuss his proposal to merge the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> departments with Labor Secretary <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> on Wednesday, when they visit a <LOCATION> Dade </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> school that is part of a highly successful pilot program that gives teachers a say in school budgets and management. `` I think we have to treat these kids as though they are workers,'' <PERSON> Shanker </PERSON> said. `` We need to create the perception that school is a good place for them.''
