<HEAD>Human Rights Group Calls On Bulgaria to Improve Human Rights</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> appealed to the Bulgarian government Tuesday for information about ethnic Turks imprisoned mainly for peacefully opposing a forced assimilation campaign. The London-based human rights group said some members of <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION>'s Turkish minority have been jailed on terrorism or espionage charges for protesting a name-changing policy which took effect four years ago, and some have been tortured. Many were among hundreds arrested in 1984 and early 1985 for resisting or protesting the assimilation campaign, which restricted language and religion and forced Turks to give up their Islamic names. `` The Bulgarian authorities have charged many with criminal charges like ` terrorism' or ` hooliganism' but <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> believes that the real reason for their imprisonment may be their non-violent opposition to the assimilation campaign,'' the report said. In addition, an increase in independent human rights activities in the past year has been followed by a crackdown on activists, <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> warned in a report. <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> said <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION> ratified in 1970 the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Covenant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Political </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION>, which guarantees free expression, association and movement. `` Amnesty International is calling on the government to end violations of these basic rights,'' it said in the report. The group seeks information on more than 150 prisoners, mostly from the 900,000-strong ethnic Turkish minority which makes up about 10 percent of the population, said the report. Since 1984, the Bulgarian government has denied that a Turkish minority exists in the country. It also says there are no human rights abuses. <PERSON> Ahmed </PERSON> <PERSON> Hasanov </PERSON> <PERSON> Aptullov </PERSON>, a 29-year-old philosophy lecturer from <ORGANIZATION> Sofia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, and three others were arrested after producing leaflets in 1986 rallying Turks to oppose the assimilation, <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> said. They were imprisoned for eight to 10 years each. <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> considers them prisoners of conscience, the human rights group's term for people who use non-violent means to express themselves. The report described in detail the cases of 11 prisoners of conscience, and said <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> seeks information on another 144 prisoners. The group said another prisoner of conscience, <PERSON> Ismail </PERSON> <PERSON> Mehmedov </PERSON> <PERSON> Hyuseinov </PERSON>, was arrested in 1985 for refusing to accept his new name and applying to emigrate to <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>. He was badly beaten in prison but released to internal exile after losing 88 pounds on a hunger strike. The government said he was freed in 1987, but <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> said it has been told he remains in exile in northwest <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION>. Other prisoners have been tortured by prolonged beating on the soles of the feet, the report said. <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> said it has long been concerned about prisoners of conscience in <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION>, and welcomed the recent dialogue begun with the Bulgarian government. It said Bulgarian authorities supplied information in 1987 after repeated reques