<FIRST>a e PM-APonTV-Timeline ADV22   02-21 0789</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP on TV-Timeline, ADV 22,0807</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv22</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wed PMs, Feb. 22</HEAD>
<HEAD>`Timeline' Presents `News' from the Past</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 What if television news had been around to report on historic events, such as the Crusades? The producers of `` Timeline'' asked that question, and the result, a six-part series on <ORGANIZATION> PBS </ORGANIZATION>, premieres tonight. The answer is _ it would look pretty dumb. The series premieres tonight with `` The Crusades, 1187.'' The other episodes, airing in coming weeks, are `` The Black Death, 1361,'' `` The <ORGANIZATION> Vikings </ORGANIZATION>, 1066,'' `` The Fall of Byzantium, 1453,'' `` The Mongol Empire, 1247'' and `` <LOCATION> Granada </LOCATION>, 1492.'' If this is what it takes to make people swallow history lessons, we're doomed. Anyone dim enough to need former network newsman <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Bell </PERSON> _ dressed in Medieval costume, no less _ to explain the Plague in sound bites, will sit still only long enough to realize this is not the <PERSON> Monty </PERSON> <PERSON> Python </PERSON> sketch it at first appears, then switch to `` Who's the Boss?'' The only immediate use for the six-part series would seem to be presenting it to caged junior high schoolers. First, there's the problem of making what is basically a historical documentary look like a news report, so there are confusing graphics on top of various scenes declaring the footage `` File'' or `` Live'' _ from the year 1187, or whatever, of course. Correspondents in period costume _ with names such as <PERSON> Owen </PERSON> of Canarfon or Siboletto of <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION> _ also confuse the viewer since they are intercut with `` interviews'' with participants in the events. Then, if that were n't enough, we're presented with explanations of past events that led up to the `` current'' situation, labeled `` 91 years ago,'' for instance. The history lesson is perfectly serious _ even though it seems <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Cleese </PERSON> will appear at any moment _ but there are lame attempts at humor. The programs are interrupted occasionally by period `` commercials,'' such as one hawking chimneys, a new concept. The dramatizations are impressive in their careful attention to authentic detail in the costumes and sets _ if not in the rather overly enthusiastic acting. The series was taped on locations in <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>. But the programs are extremely wordy. The basic problem with `` Timeline'' is that it ultimately is not like television news _ television news would never bombard viewers with so much information.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Elsewhere in television: HOW GOOD IS YOUR CHILDREN'S SHOW? _ You've got a new children's program, but you do n't know if it's good or not What do you do? <PERSON> Peggy </PERSON> <PERSON> Charren </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Children </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION>, has five questions producers and presenters of children's programming should ask themselves: 1. Does the program have something to say instead of just something to sell? 2. Would you submit it to an international animation or film festival for an award? 3. Would you put it at the top of a list for the lawyer who is defending you against a station's challenge? 4. Would parents tape it if their children were at the dentist? 5. Would you mention it by name if your child's teacher asked you what you do for a living? <PERSON> Charren </PERSON> presented the list at a recent <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION> dinner where she was awarded the Trustees' Emmy Award for her watchdog efforts on behalf of youthful viewers. ... `` BABAR'' ON <ORGANIZATION> HBO </ORGANIZATION>'' _ <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Box </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, which has gotten into the children's programming business with good results so far, is giving the beloved children's book character, <PERSON> Babar </PERSON> the elephant, his own series. The series, based on the 28 stories written by painter <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Brunhoff </PERSON> and his son, <PERSON> Laurent </PERSON>, will premiere April 2. ... THE FAMILY THAT WATCHES TOGETHER, IS N'T _ According to <ORGANIZATION> Nielsen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Media </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION>, families with pay cable and children _ not necessarily in that order _ are more than twice as likely as other households to watch more than one set at the same time. Prime time was the most popular time for watching more than one set, presumably with the kids in one room and the parents in the other. ... <ORGANIZATION> CNN </ORGANIZATION> IN <LOCATION> THE </LOCATION> <LOCATION> U.S.S.R. </LOCATION> _ <ORGANIZATION> CNN </ORGANIZATION>'s international news compendium `` CNN World Report'' made its debut on Soviet television as part of `` Mezdunardony Televestnik'' or `` <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> TV </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION>'' last month. The half-hour program, anchored by Soviet host <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Gurnov </PERSON>, utilized CNN-provided reporting on the worldwide spread of AIDS. Soviet television will continue airing its version of the program monthly until May, when it becomes a bi-weekly series. `` CNN World Report'' is comprised of reports from various broadcast news organizations around the world, and many other nations make use of the reports in their newscasts.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed PMs, Feb. 22</NOTE>
