<FIRST>a i AM-GreenConsumers Adv01   02-21 0890</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Green Consumers, Adv 01,0919</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv01</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wed AMs, March 1, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Green Consumer Movement Gains Momentum in Europe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The `` green consumer'' movement is gaining momentum in <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, and environmentalism is becoming mainstream. Now many Europeans need only to go to the neighborhood supermarket if they want organically grown vegetables, low-mercury batteries, or what have become known as environment-friendly diapers and cruelty-free cosmetics, those marketed without being tested on laboratory animals. Consumers increasingly are demanding products that do n't `` cost the earth,'' and companies are seizing the new opportunity, experts say. `` People realize that by exercising choice on the high street -LRB- main street -RRB- they can change the way the environment is treated,'' said <PERSON> Virginia </PERSON> <PERSON> Bottomley </PERSON>, a British environment official. `` There's a growing acceptance that we ca n't go on using and destroying the world's natural resources.'' She was one of 11 speakers at a recent <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> conference of officials from government, industry and environmental groups called `` Attracting the Green Consumer.'' <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Sadler </PERSON>, an advertising consultant, told the conference: `` Green issues are not just flavor of the month. This could become the world's central project for the next century.'' Here are just some of the steps governments have taken: _ The 12-nation <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> and 23 other countries have committed themselves to cutting back the use of CFCs, or chlorofluorocarbons, by 50 percent by the end of the century CFCs, used as propellants, are thought to deplete the earth's protective ozone shield. _ <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> plans a 100-lire -LRB- 8-cent -RRB- tax on consumers for each non-biodegradable plastic bag they take from the store _ The <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> is offering tax breaks to people who buy cars that meet strict anti-pollution standards _ <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> for years has put `` Blue Angel'' labels on products that meet its environmental standards The Scandinavian countries, the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> are following suit. Queen <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> has switched her fleet of cars to lead-free gasoline, and her son <PERSON> Prtince </PERSON> <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> has banned aerosol sprays from his home. Green consumerism offers many opportunities to companies, but confronts them with a complex market, the experts said. `` The highest levels of concern are shown by the more affluent groups of society,'' said <PERSON> Dorothy </PERSON> <PERSON> MacKenzie </PERSON>, a marketing expert. But `` there are lots of different green consumers. They are motivated by different concerns and have widely different patterns.'' They range from 1960s-style hippies and current-day `` guppies'' -LRB- green yuppies -RRB- to mothers concerned about their children's future, she said. The green opportunities mean companies can make money directly, by selling green products, as well as indirectly, by enhancing their reputation. `` Our reputation clearly helps our business,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Hume </PERSON>, director of <ORGANIZATION> Johnson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wax </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, the British subsidiary of the similarly named <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> household products maker. His company removed CFCs from its aerosols in 1986, a costly exercise, and labels products environment-friendly. Disposable diapers are one of the latest products to go green and earn the reputation of being environment-friendly. Procter and <PERSON> Gamble </PERSON>, joining other companies, is selling chlorine-free diapers in six countries. The chlorine-processed diapers contain tiny residues of the highly poisonous chemical dioxin. <ORGANIZATION> Safeway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, no relation to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> supermarket chain, has removed contentious or detrimental ingredients from its own products, such as artificial color in its own-brand orange soda. It also recycles its cardboard and offers its customers free, recycled paper bags. It has built a CFC-free refrigeration center in <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>. The British confectioner <ORGANIZATION> Cadbury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> is among companies that have opted for a link with a worthy cause. In 1985 it began donating a percentage of sales of a chocolate Wildlife Bar to the World Wildlife Fund to help endangered animals. The animals are depicted on the bars' labels. Research has found that consumers are willing to pay more for environment-friendly products. <PERSON> Marek </PERSON> <PERSON> Mayer </PERSON>, an expert on environmental issues, said some West German retailers are believed to charge more for products that carry the `` Blue Angel'' label, even though some of these products are cheaper to make. <PERSON> Julia </PERSON> <PERSON> Hailes </PERSON>, co-author of `` The Green Consumer Guide,'' said green products initially will cost more, but their prices will decline as they are mass-produced. Despite green consumerism's growing momentum, both consumers and companies remain reluctant to embrace it wholeheartedly, the experts said. Organic produce still represents less than 5 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Safeway </ORGANIZATION>'s total produce sales, said <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Combes </PERSON>, a director The government's Mrs. <PERSON> Bottomley </PERSON> lamented that only 2 percent of the auto fuel consumed in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> is unleaded `` People will not do what they say they do for the environment unless its very easy,'' <PERSON> Sadler </PERSON> said. `` Personal benefit may still be the key to adopting green issues. The idea of doing something for the common good is still not a motivation for people yet, unfortunately.'' The experts said the threat of consumer criticism is very real. `` There's a very great danger that we could have an inconsistency here of polluting the environment while producing green products,'' <PERSON> Hume </PERSON> said. For instance, he added, lead-free gas might reduce air pollution, but its manufacture produces at least one highly toxic byproduct. <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Guthrie </PERSON>, a manager at <ORGANIZATION> Boots </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> MicroCheck </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, a chemicals maker, said: `` Some manufacturers have made preservative-free claims when the product did n't need to be preserved in the first place. These attempts to mislead the consumer should be actively discouraged.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed AMs, March 1</NOTE>
