<HEAD>$Adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, March 5</HEAD>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 4 b&amp;w photos.
ColorFoto subscribers get 3 35mm slides.)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 EDITOR'S NOTE _ For centuries they were the playgrounds of the rich, but in recent years the lavish health spas of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> have depended mainly on the aging and infirm who could take the waters at government expense. Now the pendulum is swinging again and guess who gave it a big push. Health-conscious yuppies, known among Germans as `` Schickimickis,'' have discovered the spa scene.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</NOTE>
<NOTE>Associatred Press Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BADEN BADEN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s most-famous health spas, like this 19th century playground for the rich, royal and renowned, are enjoying a renaissance among an emerging class of European yuppies. `` Take a look _ and get looked at,'' is one of the advertising slogans luring a hedonistic crowd into the spa social scene that for the past 30 years has been dominated by the weak and aging. In a period of federal belt-tightening, the resorts that in the postwar years have focused on government-sponsored health care are now turning back to the healthy and wealthy who bestowed their original fame. A modest trimming of social security benefits that took effect with the new year promises to cut into the ranks of 8.4 million `` cure guests'' who take the waters each year in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. But administrators of the most distinguished baths say they had long been expecting fiscal conservatism to catch up with the cushy health care system. Some, like <PERSON> Baden </PERSON> <PERSON> Baden </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Bad </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aachen </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wiesbaden </LOCATION>, have begun catering to a new generation of guests, a younger crowd of well-heeled professionals known among Germans as `` Schickimickis.'' Sequined and tuxedoed, the elite envoys of the 30-to-40 set saunter and gamble in the path of <PERSON> Feodor </PERSON> <PERSON> Dostoevski </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kaiser </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilhelm </PERSON> in <PERSON> Baden </PERSON> <PERSON> Baden </PERSON>'s glittering casino. Dwindling in number are the elderly and ailing bingo players in an adjacent parlor of the Kurhaus. A sprawling seven-pool, glass-enclosed `` bathing temple'' completed three years ago draws 1,500 guests a day, increasingly from among younger couples and singles who come here for long weekends to play tennis, relax and flaunt their newfound prosperity. <PERSON> Hans </PERSON> <PERSON> Berg </PERSON>, manager of the German <ORGANIZATION> Bathing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> office in <LOCATION> Bonn </LOCATION>, says the spas are attracting a broader group of guests and becoming less dependent on the publicly insured clientele. Under the 1956 legislation that set up today's elaborate social security net, West Germans are entitled to a spa treatment as often as every three years if their doctors recommend it. Until this year, the federally funded health insurance network paid the full cost of a three - or four-week bathing cure for those recuperating from illness or taking a respite from the stresses of work or family life Cure clients must now pay 10 percent of the cost of their treatments, which run an average of $ 2,750 for four weeks, plus most of their hotel and food expenses. `` We do n't know exactly what effect the changes in the law will have on the industry, and we hope this is n't too strong a blow,'' <PERSON> Berg </PERSON> says. `` But we have been enjoying a steady growth over the past year or two of younger visitors, and by younger I mean those in their 30s who want to go away for a few days for a small vacation rather than a cure.'' <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Bartholemy </PERSON>, <PERSON> Baden </PERSON> <PERSON> Baden </PERSON>'s spa association general manager, contends the cutbacks are shortsighted. `` Some of those who would benefit from rest and recuperation will put off taking a cure because of the expense, then end up in the hospital which will cost more for a few days than a preventative cure,'' he says. But spa administrators expect that a trend among younger Germans to take better care of their health promises to more than compensate for an expected drop in visits by guests on social security. `` The changes in our clientele have had a positive economic effect,'' says <PERSON> Sigrun </PERSON> <PERSON> Lang </PERSON>, chairwoman of <PERSON> Baden </PERSON> <PERSON> Baden </PERSON>'s spa association. `` While the guest here for a publicly funded cure is often on a restricted budget during his four-week stay, those staying for a three-day convention or a long weekend tend to spend a lot in the shops and the casino.'' A slender, 40-ish executive, Mrs. <PERSON> Lang </PERSON> says the more successful spas are cashing in on the younger generation's growing absorption with health and appearance. Despite a nationwide unemployment rate of 8.5 percent, a new affluence is visible among the younger, college-educated crowd in major cities like <LOCATION> Hamburg </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Munich </LOCATION>. And like their baby boom contemporaries in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, West Germans in their 30s and early 40s are gradually moving into the upper echelons of government and industry. Foreign guests continue to account for more than a quarter of the spa patronage, with wealthy Americans, Arabs, Japanese and Europeans replacing the Russian nobility of the last century. Fewer turn to the mystic healing effects of water to cure serious illnesses these days, but the younger generations frequenting the spas are bringing along new health challenges for the resorts to tackle. The opulent art deco complex at <LOCATION> Bad </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Nauheim </LOCATION>, for example, now offers a program to break the smoking habit. Bad Mergentheim, nestled in a scenic valley of vineyards along the famous Romantic Road, attracts a new clientele with its weight-reduction course. Bad Aachen, at the three-nation crossroads with <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Holland </LOCATION> where <PERSON> Charlemagne </PERSON> took the waters 1,200 years ago, now offers stress-management clinics. Managers of smaller spas and the hotels and restaurants supported by cure guests are nervous about the effects of the streamlining. They point out that only a few dozen of the 264 officially recognized health spas in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> are esteemed enough to get by on the clientele that pays its own way. `` There is no other industry here except the spas,'' says <PERSON> Elke </PERSON> <PERSON> Requeer </PERSON>, treatment director at the city cure house in <LOCATION> Bad </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Muenstereifel </LOCATION>, a scenic hamlet in the foothills of the <LOCATION> Eifel </LOCATION> near the border with <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>. `` We do n't get a lot of younger visitors here because most of our patients are elderly and the atmosphere must remain quiet.'' School director <PERSON> Anita </PERSON> <PERSON> Meinhardt </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Fulda </LOCATION>, taking a cure at <LOCATION> Baden </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Baden </LOCATION> this winter at her own expense, said the federal cutbacks are unlikely to deter those strongly in need of rest and may encourage more personal responsibility about one's health. Referring to her countrymen's propensity to drink and smoke more than other Europeans, she contended that, `` One should n't expect the government to provide an all-expense-paid cure for a lifetime of bad living habits.''
</TEXT>
