<HEAD>L'ANSE, Mich.: converting pagans.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 `` I'm not demeaning Father Baraga. Anybody bringing <PERSON> Christ </PERSON> would enrich us. His every effort was to build us up, which he really did accidentally by preserving our language. He was a man who was sincere, which made him in the Indian way a holy man.'' <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> LaPointe </PERSON>, a 58-year-old Ojibwa, grew up with the <LOCATION> Baraga </LOCATION> legend, handed down from his father and grandfather. `` They held him in reverence,'' he says. `` One of my earliest memories was seeing a picture of him.'' Baraga built homes and schools for the Ojibwa and purchased 500 acres of land for the tribe, <PERSON> LaPointe </PERSON> says. Just recently the <LOCATION> Keweenaw </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tribe </LOCATION> obtained the deed for the land from the <LOCATION> Marquette </LOCATION> diocese. Today, <LOCATION> Baraga </LOCATION>'s outpost at L'Anse is surrounded by an Ojibwa reservation where children read their history in the language <PERSON> Baraga </PERSON> penned. Summers at the shrine are crowded with tourists, but winter leaves the Ellicos alone with a friendly Doberman pinscher named <PERSON> Hans </PERSON> and the silent Baraga statue, shrouded in snow. Schoolchildren come out now and then to burn candles by the shrine. A state plaque nearby marks an ancient Indian trail that heads south to <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>. At least one missionary is believed to have died on the frozen path. This is the time of year the Ellicos, who have tended the shrine for 14 years, notice the increasing cold and dream of retiring and moving south. <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> and his brother once envisioned a tourist motel and restaurant on the bluff overlooking <LOCATION> Keweenaw </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>, but his brother died and the <ORGANIZATION> Bishop </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Baraga </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> asked if he would donate land for the shrine. <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Ellico </PERSON> agreed. Artist <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>'s robed priest stands high on a giant metallic cloud, atop copper arches that end in five tepees, one for each of the Indian missions <LOCATION> Baraga </LOCATION> founded. To <PERSON> Walling </PERSON>, <PERSON> Baraga </PERSON>'s own life was the greatest show of divine intervention. `` That he survived under the conditions he lived _ that was more a miracle than anything else,'' she says. `` He traveled from L'Anse to <LOCATION> Duluth </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION>, on snowshoes. His eyes froze shut and he survived with no harm.'' <PERSON> Walling </PERSON> has given <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> other evidence, though. From there, a Franciscan priest, <PERSON> Father </PERSON> <PERSON> Bruno </PERSON> <PERSON> Korosak </PERSON>, sends them on to the Sacred Congregation of Saints. `` There are over 110 very strong cases of miracles or intercessions,'' <PERSON> Walling </PERSON> says. One involved Baraga County Clerk <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Lambert </PERSON>, who led the effort in the early 1970s to build the <LOCATION> Baraga </LOCATION> shrine, <PERSON> Thoren </PERSON> says. <PERSON> Lambert </PERSON>, who was crippled with arthritis at 28, died last year. `` He was totally invalid and then he walked,'' <PERSON> Thoren </PERSON> says. `` I believe the statue was done in 1971 in thanksgiving.'' The Catholic community has not waited for <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> to begin sending prayers to <LOCATION> Baraga </LOCATION>. The faithful carefully pass among themselves relics of his existence: thread from his woolen socks and splinters of wood from his burial casket. A Hubbell woman's cancer completely vanished after she prayed to <LOCATION> Baraga </LOCATION> with thread from his socks in her hands, <PERSON> Walling </PERSON> says. `` My mother had a thread,'' <PERSON> Thoren </PERSON> says. `` When my brother became a sky diver, she gave it to him. Then he gave it to a friend who was dying of cancer.'' The cancer victim died, but the thread was preserved, a precious token. If the miracles are accepted, Baraga's writings must be presented in a document that explains the context of his work, a process <PERSON> Walling </PERSON> says is two-thirds complete. Then the real journey begins, as the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> considers Baraga first for veneration, beatification and finally canonization.
