<FIRST>a a BC-WKD--FilmReviews Adv00   02-21 1102</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Film Reviews, Adv 00,1137</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>At the Movies: ``Lean on Me''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>, the principal of <ORGANIZATION> Eastside </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Paterson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, decided that a baseball bat was as good an educational tool as books. His controversial tactics are the focus of the new <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bros. </ORGANIZATION> film `` Lean on Me.'' The movie is reviewed this week by education writer <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitgang </PERSON>, who has covered the <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> controversy, and film critic <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>, in side-by-side reviews.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Anyone who has ever met <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>, the principal of <ORGANIZATION> Eastside </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Paterson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, knows that he would never allow a film crew into his school unless for the greater glory of <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>. This is, after all, the same <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> who in 1987 virtually barred a state monitoring team from inspecting his building. So it's hardly a surprise that `` Lean on Me,'' a new <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bros. </ORGANIZATION> film shot on location at <LOCATION> Eastside </LOCATION> and purporting to be based on the `` true story'' of the tough principal, turns out to be little more than blackboard jungle propaganda aimed at vindicating <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>'s bat-and-bullhorn educational methods <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bros. </ORGANIZATION> has sunk a long way since last April when it made its commendable foray into the school world with the vastly superior `` Stand and Deliver,'' a film with twice the plot and a hundred times more character development than this latest. `` Stand and Deliver'' was about a high school math teacher in a <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> barrio school who proved that inner city kids respond to the same kinds of positive things that rich kids do: adults who really care. <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>, by contrast, captured headlines in recent years as the principal who restored order to an inner-city school described by local prosecutors as a `` cauldron of violence.'' In the seven years <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> has run Eastside, he has indeed tamed this once graffiti-scarred school. His methods shocked some, but pleased many others, including then-U.S. Secretary <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> whose frequent praise helped make <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> a national celebrity. He prowled the hallways with a baseball bat and bullhorn, suspended hundreds of students, and made it clear to all that the sign in his office, `` One Way: My way'' _ applied to teachers and students alike. `` Lean on Me'' paints <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> as a principal who bleeds for his kids, but will stop at nothing, including breaking labor and fire laws, cursing out his superiors, and humiliating teachers, to achieve his aims. <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> won headlines as a black educator who blamed his school's problems on a failed social welfare system Hardly have the opening credits finished rolling before the film has made sure no one has missed any of these points. It opens with a brief shot of Eastside High in more idyllic days. In 1967, the school was mostly white; boys wore ties. <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>, then a young teacher, wore a dashiki. Twenty years later, we see a very different Eastside, with graffiti covering anything standing still long enough to be spray-painted, girls openly molested, drugs freely dispensed, fights commonplace. Into the breach steps <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>. His challenge: brush aside the small-minded politicians and school board, restore order, and raise standardized test scores quickly enough to avoid a state takeover of the school. Hey, no sweat. <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> <PERSON> Freeman </PERSON> turns in a credible performance as <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>, capturing nicely <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>'s self-righteousness. The script by <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Schiffer </PERSON> does n't leave much room for character development, but that was n't the point of this film, anyway. <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> himself had this to say of <PERSON> Freeman </PERSON> as filming proceeded last June: `` He's a good actor but I do n't think anybody can fully portray me. There's only one <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>.'' How true. _ By <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitgang </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> Education Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 If any critics' organization offered an award for The Most Manipulative Director, the Lifetime Achievement Award would surely go to <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Avildsen </PERSON>. Consider his ability to rouse audiences to anger, revulsion and especially, the overwhelming joy of victory over impossible odds in such films as `` Joe,'' `` Save the Tiger,'' `` Rocky,'' `` Neighbors'' and `` The Karate Kid.'' The new <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bros. </ORGANIZATION> release, `` Lean on Me,'' is quintessential <PERSON> Avildsen </PERSON>. From the very first frame, he grabs the viewers and plays their emotions with the skill of a disc jockey at a disco turntable. You cheer and weep tears of joy despite the realization that you are being shamelessly used. The film is based on the headline-making career of <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>, the black educator who turned the <LOCATION> Paterson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Eastside </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> from a ghetto jungle into a model of achievement, wielding a symbolic baseball bat. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Schiffer </PERSON>'s script obviously takes liberties with the facts, since it is orchestrated in a series of audience-stirring sequences. <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> -LRB- <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> <PERSON> Freeman </PERSON> -RRB- is a zealous teacher whose fierce temper and outspokenness has relegated him to being principal of a white grammar school. When Eastside High is threatened with a takeover by the state because of a dismal academic record, the mayor -LRB- <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON> -RRB- and school superintendent -LRB- <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Guillaume </PERSON> -RRB- reluctantly enlist <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> as Eastside principal. <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> begins by ousting all the drug dealers and goof-offs, painting over the graffiti, and haranguing both students and teachers. He goes overboard, alienating his staff and making an enemy of a power-hungry activist -LRB- <PERSON> Lynne </PERSON> <PERSON> Thigpen </PERSON> -RRB-. <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> is jailed for locking the school doors -LRB- to keep out drug dealers -RRB-, but you can guess who triumphs in the end. <PERSON> Schiffer </PERSON>, who also wrote the slambang `` Colors,'' has provided a messy screenplay, overloaded with shouted speeches and offering an improbably sentimental climax that would make <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Capra </PERSON> seem like <PERSON> Chekhov </PERSON>. But for those willing to leave cynicism at home, `` Lean on Me'' can be a moving experience, thanks in large part to <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> <PERSON> Freeman </PERSON>'s powerful presence. He is a marvel of raw energy commanding force. <PERSON> Beverly </PERSON> <PERSON> Tyler </PERSON> has the relatively thankless role of <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>'s long-suffering assistant but she performs admirably The students are uniformly great. <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> Twain </PERSON> produced the film which is rated PG-13, mostly for language and violent action. Refreshingly, the film makes little use of expletives, which might have abounded in such a film. Running time: 104 minutes. _ By <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Motion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Picture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> rating definitions: G _ General audiences. All ages admitted. PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be suitable for children. PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young children. R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult guardian. X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age restrictions.
</TEXT>
