 `` Honky Tonk Angel'' -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> MCA </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ <PERSON> Patty </PERSON> <PERSON> Loveless </PERSON> <PERSON> Patty </PERSON> <PERSON> Loveless </PERSON>' crystal clear voice lends a subtle, rather than overpowering, quality to her music. So `` <PERSON> Honky </PERSON> <PERSON> Tonk </PERSON> <PERSON> Angel </PERSON>,'' her third album, does n't score an immediate knockout. But it's an enjoyable, if not spectacular, record that sounds better with repeated listening. Loveless works in the same musical territory as such hip country traditionalists as <PERSON> Emmylou </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>, <PERSON> Rodney </PERSON> <PERSON> Crowell </PERSON> and <PERSON> Rosanne </PERSON> <PERSON> Cash </PERSON>. She's at her best, however, with the pop-leaning ballads `` If You Think'' and `` I'm on Your Side.'' Also worth hearing is her rendition of the great `` Do n't Toss Us Away.'' Her version, with backround vocals by <PERSON> Crowell </PERSON>, is more understated than the Lone Justice original but no less powerful as Loveless makes a plea for keeping a romance alive even as all around `` it seems like everyone we've known, their love's grown cold.'' Loveless' band, featuring fiddler <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> and the always impressive <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> on guitar, is solid throughout on an album that _ sort of like a good concert opening act _ gives the sense of hearing an artist who may have something great in her future. _ By <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Rice </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
