<TEXT>
 Symphonies No. 24, 26, 27 and 30 by <PERSON> Wolfgang </PERSON> <PERSON> Amadeus </PERSON> <PERSON> Mozart </PERSON>; <ORGANIZATION> Prague </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orchestra </ORGANIZATION>, conducted by Sir <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Mackerras </PERSON> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Telarc </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- For listeners not enchanted with performances on original instruments but who want fresh-sounding, more authentic versions of pre-20th century works, there is a middle course. Sir <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Mackerras </PERSON> and the <ORGANIZATION> Prague </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orchestra </ORGANIZATION> take it in this Telarc recording of four middle symphonies by the 17-year-old <PERSON> Mozart </PERSON>. The orchestra is scaled back, a harpsichord added and the style of playing is that of original instrument recordings, though the instruments are modern. The strings make more biting attacks and lean into the beginning of notes, and the flutes and oboes leave out vibrato. The sound is brisk and lean and full of life, and the musicians play with a controlled exuberance. There is a little too much echo to the sound, a result probably of the recording site, the Castle of <LOCATION> Dobris </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Mackerras </PERSON> sometimes lets things move along a little too briskly, though there are loving moments, especially in the masterful slow movement of No. 27, perhaps the best part of the disc. The main theme is a descending string passage capped by plucked notes in the cello, which become their own counter theme in the next section. As <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Malloch </PERSON>'s fine linear notes point out, these symphonies are numbered out of chronological order: Nos. 26 and 27 were written before <PERSON> Mozart </PERSON>'s July-September 1773 visit to <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>, and Nos. 24 and 30 after. Oddly, No. 24 sounds the earliest, with its simple descending three-chord main theme in the first movement. No. 26 sounds the most operatic, and was indeed used as an overture to a play. No. 30 is full of humor, a light-hearted romp in the opening Molto Allegro movement, followed by a stately Andantino, Menuetto and Haydenesque surprise ending in the final Presto. The <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> trip was <PERSON> Mozart </PERSON>'s third to the European music capital. As a 7-year-old prodigy, he jumped into the lap of Empress <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> Theresa </PERSON> and gave her a kiss for her praise. The next time, he got a gold watch. In 1773, he got another audience _ but not the court appointment he had hoped for. The empress in a letter compared the ever-touring genius to a traveling beggar. _ By <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Wakin </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
