<HEAD>Star Watch: Will the Real Joe Clark Please Stand Up</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It could have been an actor's nightmare: starring in a movie while the man you're portraying is always there, peeping over your shoulder. But for <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> <PERSON> Freeman </PERSON>, the results were great. <PERSON> Freeman </PERSON>, who received an Academy Award nomination last year for his supporting role as the terrifying pimp in `` Street Smart,'' is the star of <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bros. </ORGANIZATION>' `` Lean on Me.'' He plays the role of <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> principal who turned a drug-ridden wasteland into a model high school with the symbolic weapons of a baseball bat and a bullhorn. Not only is <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> alive and functioning at Eastside High in <LOCATION> Paterson </LOCATION>. He was also present while `` Lean on Me'' was being shot at Eastside. `` <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> was there before we started,'' says <PERSON> Freeman </PERSON>. `` Since we filmed in the school and school was in session, he was there every day, doing his job. `` You want to know if that was daunting? Yes. Incredibly daunting the first week and a half or two. I did n't know how I was going to do it.'' How much of the performance is <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> <PERSON> Freeman </PERSON> and how much is <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>? `` All of the performance is <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> <PERSON> Freeman </PERSON>,'' he replied. `` What <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> <PERSON> Freeman </PERSON> could bring in the way of <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> was largely due to <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>. He was very available to me, extremely helpful, very supportive. He made it easy, despite my own sense of inadequacy.'' But <PERSON> Freeman </PERSON> still had to create a character, not merely imitate <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>. `` That's what I lost sight of,'' he admitted. `` I went into this watching him and thinking, ` I got to be <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>,' rather than, ` I've got to give a performance.' I had to straighten myself out on that. It was like trying to make a Studebaker look like a Buick.'' <PERSON> Freeman </PERSON> was pleased to report that <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> has seen the film and has given his seal of approval. `` That's the seal that counts,'' said <PERSON> Freeman </PERSON>. `` I really wanted him to like the movie. I like him a lot.'' Not everyone agrees. <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> was tagged `` Crazy Joe'' because of some of his tactics, including the chaining of school exit doors to keep out drug dealers. Or his initial act of expelling 300 under-achieving and trouble-making pupils. <PERSON> Freeman </PERSON>, however, dismisses <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>'s critics. `` He is universally beloved by his students, and that's all that counts. People who disagree with him are meaningless. They're off in some kind of ivory tower; I do n't think they even know what he did.'' Some might argue that <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> has been operating a fascist state. `` So what?'' answers <PERSON> Freeman </PERSON>. `` What do you think a school is? It's not a democracy. You ca n't teach democracy if you ca n't catch the attention of the students. No school I ever went to was -LRB- a democracy -RRB-.'' His schools were in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Side </LOCATION>, an area not unlike <PERSON> Paterson </PERSON>. <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> had been born in <LOCATION> Greenwood </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miss. </LOCATION>, but his family moved north when he was young. He remembers school as being much more orderly than what <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> faces. `` The streets were what I had to negotiate; the schools were not a problem,'' he remarked. `` Once you got through the doors of school, you were safe. There the teachers had control. `` What -LRB- ` Lean on Me' -RRB- represents is what happened to schools, particularly in the inner cities, in the'60s and'70s. The schools were taken over by the students, and the teachers were shortchanged. Their caseloads and classrooms were entirely too large. Their ability to discipline miscreants was undermined by <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> rulings about corporal punishment in schools. And their salaries were so low that they became second-class citizens.'' <PERSON> Freeman </PERSON> first fell in love with acting in the third grade, when he portrayed <PERSON> Little </PERSON> <PERSON> Boy </PERSON> <PERSON> Blue </PERSON> in a class pageant. In the seventh grade he won the <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> state prize as best actor in a drama contest. But his real ambition was to become a `` hotshot pilot with a scarf around my neck and strafe the enemy's flag.'' In the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> he became a radar technician instead. After his discharge he realized what he really wanted to do was act, and he enrolled at <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> to learn the basics. His first professional job was dancing at the 1964 <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION>'s Fair, then he joined a touring company of `` The Royal Hunt of the Sun.'' <PERSON> Freeman </PERSON> managed to earn a living in plays such as `` Hello, Dolly'' -LRB- with <LOCATION> Pearl </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bailey </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Cab </PERSON> <PERSON> Calloway </PERSON> -RRB- and `` Purlie'' and in TV shows such as <ORGANIZATION> PBS </ORGANIZATION>'s `` The <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION>.'' Then in 1980 the jobs inexplicably stopped. He still does n't know why, except maybe he was too outspoken in rejecting material he deemed substandard. The drought lasted two years, and he credits <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Newman </PERSON> with helping him get work again, casting him in a film. The big breakthrough came with `` Street Smart.'' `` I always wanted to play a pimp,'' he admitted, `` and this guy was real.'' Critics thought so. <PERSON> Pauline </PERSON> <PERSON> Kael </PERSON> even theorized in The New Yorker: `` Is <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> <PERSON> Freeman </PERSON> the greatest American Actor?'' `` Street Smart,'' which starred <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Reeve </PERSON>, was released early in 1987 to so-so business. <PERSON> Freeman </PERSON>'s achievement might have faded from view except that <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> critic <PERSON> Sheila </PERSON> <PERSON> Benson </PERSON> suggested to <ORGANIZATION> Cannon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Films </ORGANIZATION> publicist <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON> <PERSON> Kwit </PERSON> that his performance deserved an Oscar campaign. His reaction to the Academy nomination? `` I felt fine. It was like having a pat on the back and ` Well done.' You sort of kick the dirt and say, ` Aw gee, thanks' -LRB- laughing -RRB- and try to hold onto your sense of self and not go off flying half-cocked It's just a pat on the back.''
