<HEAD>Nashville Sound: ``Streets of Bakersfield'' Helps Career</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM KELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ELK, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Homer Joy recently got a call from a woman who had once scolded him for his noisy guitar playing and singing. Joy, 43, said the former neighbor recalled the confident young musician's reply 35 years ago that she would n't yell at him after she heard his songs on the radio. The apologetic call came after his song, `` Streets of <LOCATION> Bakersfield </LOCATION>,'' was nominated for a Grammy as country song of the year and <PERSON> Joy </PERSON> was nominated as songwriter of the year. Now, <PERSON> Joy </PERSON> hopes the song that also helped <PERSON> Buck </PERSON> <PERSON> Owens </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dwight </PERSON> <PERSON> Yoakam </PERSON> receive a Grammy nomination for country duo of the year will also help him find a record company to distribute a gospel album. It was 16 years ago that <PERSON> Joy </PERSON> wrote and recorded `` The Streets of <LOCATION> Bakersfield </LOCATION>,'' about the frustration he felt while recording a `` sound-alike'' album of <PERSON> Hank </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> Sr. songs at <LOCATION> Owens </LOCATION><LOCATION> ' </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bakersfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, studio `` It just was n't what I wanted to do,'' <PERSON> Joy </PERSON> said during a recent interview. But because he was under contract with <ORGANIZATION> Buck </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Owens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprises </ORGANIZATION>, he finished the project, then insisted that producer <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON> listen to him play a song he'd written. `` I really got kind of redneck about it,'' <PERSON> Joy </PERSON> said, but the end result was that <PERSON> Owens </PERSON> heard the song and loved it, and had Joy record it. `` The Streets of <LOCATION> Bakersfield </LOCATION>'' was a Top 10 hit in 1973 for <PERSON> Joy </PERSON>, a native of Heber Springs, Ark. Joy had another hit single with `` John Law'' in 1974, and <PERSON> Owens </PERSON>, <PERSON> Freddie </PERSON> <PERSON> Hart </PERSON> and other big-name country singers were recording his songs. He performed on the same bill with <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION> stars such as <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>, <PERSON> Mel </PERSON> <PERSON> Tillis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Tanya </PERSON> <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON>. The version of `` The Streets of <LOCATION> Bakersfield </LOCATION>'' recorded last year by <PERSON> Owens </PERSON> and <PERSON> Yoakam </PERSON> hit the top of the country charts. But in the years between his version and the latest version of the song, Joy hit rock bottom. Joy said he and <PERSON> Owens </PERSON> mutually agreed to end his contract in 1976 because of `` artistic differences.'' After that, he proved unable to cope with the pressures, traveling and temptations of being a rising star. After <PERSON> Joy </PERSON> and his wife of 15 years, <PERSON> Lois </PERSON>, divorced in 1978, his life changed. `` I sold 4.5 million records, and then I had everything I owned in a cardboard box in 1983,'' <PERSON> Joy </PERSON> said. `` It was a real disaster.'' But the down-and-out wanderer, who as a boy would sneak out of Saturday movie matinees to sing with <ORGANIZATION> Salvation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> bands on streetcorners in <LOCATION> Spokane </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>, said he got a dose of salvation that helped him recover and gave him a new outlook on his music. `` I accepted the Lord six years ago,'' <PERSON> Joy </PERSON> said. He and <PERSON> Lois </PERSON> remarried in June 1983, and the following year a daughter, <PERSON> Bethany </PERSON>, was born. The Joys have seven children. Along with his wife, sons <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Preston </PERSON> accompany their father on the album of gospel songs he's recording at a studio in <LOCATION> Spokane </LOCATION> `` My wife and I said a prayer a year ago, and it could n't have been more than three weeks later that <PERSON> Dwight </PERSON> and Buck did -LRB- the song -RRB- on the Country Music Awards anniversary show,'' he said. Their record was released last July and hit No. 1 on Oct. 15, but <PERSON> Joy </PERSON> said that was just a start. `` I believed ` Streets of <LOCATION> Bakersfield </LOCATION>' was No. 1 with a bullet, that it being No. 1 was just really the beginning of things,'' he said. `` And it's turned out to be true. `` It's been good for everybody this song has touched, and we're really thankful Our prayer was that we could have a way to finance our gospel album.'' For that project, <PERSON> Joy </PERSON> picked the 10 best songs he's written since he became a Christian six years ago. They are songs he's sung in performances at missions, penitentiaries and Christian services at rodeos. `` I have n't ever written a song that is n't based on truth,'' he said, including his old songs about getting drunk or stoned, womanizing and `` all those other kind of things. But I do n't believe -LRB- in those things -RRB- now. `` There was a time when I did, and I lived like that. So now we try to live what we write now.'' Joy still enjoys playing `` secular'' music, and he says his gospel songs are n't an attempt to `` stuff the Bible down people's throats `` We just try to do what we believe in and hope it will touch people, like ` The Streets of <LOCATION> Bakersfield </LOCATION>' touched a whole lot of people.'' He's well aware that the success of a song revived after 16 years does n't guarantee a good response for a new gospel album. `` This thing, with ` Streets of <LOCATION> Bakersfield </LOCATION>,' will get it listened to,'' <PERSON> Joy </PERSON> said. `` But I'm not ignorant, and I know that the album has to stand on its own, aside from anything else. And I believe it will.''
