<HEAD>Handicapped Helping Others Like Themselves</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCIA DUNN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Karl </PERSON> <PERSON> Fuls </PERSON> was angry and frustrated after losing his legs to circulatory problems. `` What I needed was to talk to me now,'' he says. `` Therapists, counselors, doctors, social workers, nobody helped me. How much money I could have saved. How many dead ends I could have avoided.'' Savvier now and far more self-sufficient, <PERSON> Fuls </PERSON> last August set up <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broken </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wing </ORGANIZATION>, a non-profit organization that matches the newly disabled with a person of the same sex, age, background and handicap to discuss strategies for coping. `` Everybody's got questions,'' Fuls, 62, said, sitting in a motorized chair at the <ORGANIZATION> Rehabilitation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> during a recent meeting. Three of the 16 people were in wheelchairs, three had canes and several wore leg braces. `` They're not going to ask a doctor. They're not going to ask a therapist. They will ask questions to people like themselves. How do you put makeup on? How do you take a shower? Is my sex life over? Things like this,'' he said. `` It's all new. I cry. Being with somebody like you helps. You can even laugh,'' said <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Tomko </PERSON>, a 50-year-old grocery employee who sought moral support _ and practical advice _ from <ORGANIZATION> Broken </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wing </ORGANIZATION> members after her right leg was amputated abovethe knee last fall because of a blood clot. Her parents, with whom she lives, accompany their only child to meetings. `` It affects me, too. I thought I was going to die,'' <PERSON> Eleanor </PERSON> <PERSON> Tomko </PERSON>, 71, said, her eyes filling with tears. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> McCrorey </PERSON>, 57, whose left side has been paralyzed for eight years because of a stroke, thrives on helping others. The former engineer regularly chats with an advertising executive who's recovering from a stroke `` It's just good to talk about our mutual problems. It's like losing half of your body and dragging it along with you. Your body commits suicide. `` It's good to have hope. There's light at the end of the tunnel.'' Occupational therapist <PERSON> Annie </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broken </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wing </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> secretary, acknowledges there are innumerable support groups to which the handicapped can turn. But they operate on `` a communication or verbal level. `` They get together. They meet. They discuss and emotionally they may feel better about their disabilities.'' The Broken Wing offers `` more than just emotional support and conversation. We are out there to provide a service, to physically make people more independent,'' <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Fuls </PERSON> had no idea how much he'd learned about coping, most of it `` the hard way,'' until 1984 when he was leafing through his diary. He began writing about his health problems a year before being diagnosed with arteriosclerosis. After his fourth and final amputation in 1982, for example, his wheelchair rolled backward down a ramp outside his house. Only later did he learn he needed a special chair for amputees that accounts for the imbalance. `` I was mad,'' he said. `` It made me start thinking.'' Soon afterward, the idea for a network to nurture independence was born. After several years of research and planning, The Broken Wing finally was chartered last August with headquarters at Fuls' home in suburban White Oak. Forty strong and growing, <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broken </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wing </ORGANIZATION> is seeking grants for office space and a computer system that would link the longtime disabled to the newly handicapped, eventually nationwide. Since late January, <PERSON> Fuls </PERSON> has been talking to support groups in search of volunteers. His message is simple: `` Do they remember how hard it was for them to adjust to a handicapped lifestyle and would they be willing to have someone else benefit from their experience?''
</TEXT>
