<HEAD>Budworm Infestation Slowing In Pacific Northwest Forests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAKER, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Adverse weather, <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> `` search-and-destroy'' missions and its own insatiable appetite have slowed the advance of the Western spruce budworm that has spread across millions of acres this decade. `` The outbreaks are clearly on the decline,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Hadfield </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. The infestation has been `` the worst one that we have ever experienced, in terms of the extent of area defoliated and damage caused.'' The tiny brown caterpillar was first spotted in 1980 on 5,000 acres near Cove, Ore. It has spread through <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, primarily east of the Cascades, feeding on needles of fir and spruce and destroying vast numbers of `` understory'' firs growing in the shadow of mature trees. `` The effects will continue to be felt as long as 70 years out because of the effect on the growth of trees,'' <PERSON> Hadfield </PERSON> said. Adverse weather at critical developmental stages and <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> eradication efforts using chemical and biological pesticides have helped reduce the infestation. In addition, trees in areas where the budworm has been present for several years are so damaged that they ca n't sustain the insect. Budworms defoliated 2.8 million acres last year, down from 4.2 million in 1987 and from a peak 6 million in 1986. `` We ar still predicting a very extensive area of defoliation in 1989, even though the intensity of the defoliation, by and large, will be pretty light,'' <PERSON> Hadfield </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> plans to test a new biological pesticide, Bacillus thuringiensis, which homes in on budworms, on two plots of 1,000 and 10,000 acres in <ORGANIZATION> Wallowa-Whitman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> in northeastern <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Medical Imaging Techniques Used to Identify Mummies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It took modern radiological techniques to take the wraps off two mummies at the <ORGANIZATION> Albany </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> History </ORGANIZATION> and Art, demonstrating that the bodies were of a man and a woman _ and that the woman had a fake toe. The toe, possibly made of a ceramic material, may have been the woman's ticket to the afterlife, said curator <PERSON> Tammis </PERSON> <PERSON> Groft </PERSON>. Egyptians believed people had to be physically intact to enter the hereafter and attempts were often made to restore missing body parts during mummification, <PERSON> Groft </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Albany </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> radiologists used standard X-rays and computed tomography scans _ which provide a computer-enhanced cross-section image of a body _ to study the mummies, one of which was only partially wrapped. That mummy was a man, as museum experts had suspected since acquiring the mummies in 1909. It may have been a priest known as Ankhefenmut who was buried in the temple of Mut at <LOCATION> Karnak </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Thebes </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Groft </PERSON> said. `` We were pretty sure the partially unwrapped mummy was a male,'' he said. `` The X-rays confirmed it, showing a male pelvis and genitalia. But the wrapped mummy remained a mystery, until we saw the X-rays.'' The radiology tests showed that both are from the 21st Egyptian dynasty, circa 1085 to 945 B.C. Both probably died of natural causes, experts theorize, since the tests did n't reveal any trauma to their bodies. It's estimated that the man died in his 50s or 60s and that the woman was about a decade younger.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Researchers Hope Long-Ignored Plant Will Be Rediscovered As Food</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A wild legume that has been eaten in eastern <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> for nearly 5,000 years needs less fertilizer than potatoes and yields three times the crude protein, says a researcher who sees it as a food crop. The `` groundnut'' or `` rosary,'' Apios americana, is a small climbing vine that produces clusters of edible pea-like seed pods and tubers. It grows along sandy creek banks, through bushes and over fallen trees. `` Historically, the plant is important because ... very few crops native to <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> have been domesticated,'' said horticulturalist <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Blackmon </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Louisiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s Agricultural Experiment Station A legume, like peas, peanuts and soybeans, the groundnut produces nitrogen and so needs less fertilizer than some food plants, <PERSON> Blackmon </PERSON> said. The plant can survive frost and other conditions unsuitable for many other crops. The tubers taste like a cross between an Irish potato and a peanut when boiled, and can be used in casseroles, corn bread and stir-fry cooking. Work is just beginning on recipes and other uses for the groundnuts, which are edible but harder to produce and might be processed into flour. <PERSON> Blackmon </PERSON> has been joined by researchers at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Minnesota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carolina </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. He began sending seeds to home gardeners in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and 16 other countries in 1986, with mixed results. `` These were wild seeds and some of the wild seeds were just not productive,'' he said. `` A lot of times you'll have a gardener who'll be real clever and will come up with something that's productive. <PERSON> Blackmon </PERSON> is trying to develop a plant with a more compact vine and with tubers closer to the stem to facilitate mechanical harvesting. `` I think that in some places it might be very beneficial to the world food supply,'' he said. `` The thing will stay stored in the ground, -LRB- so -RRB- you do n't have to store it. You can pull it when you need it.''
</TEXT>
