 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit narrowed to $ 137.34 billion in 1988, the government announced in a report economists said showed how far <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> must go before its trade problems are solved. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Friday that exports, led by a surge in manufactured goods, shot up a dramatic 26.8 percent last year to an all-time high of $ 322.22 billion. This increase supplied much of the economy's momentum in 1988 as factories hired more workers and expanded production facilities to meet the export demand.
