</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rising auto loan defaults have bitten into profits at <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, partly as a consequence of the longer terms the big automakers have been offering on new car credit. The trend has some lenders taking a closer look at credit requirements before approving car loans to consumers, who have become increasingly burdened with debt in recent years, and encouraging buyers to cut their loan requirements.
