<SECOND>PM-OPEC,0583</SECOND>
<HEAD>Subroto Says Non-OPEC Nations Likely to Cut Production</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subroto as one name is cq.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Independent oil-exporting nations are likely to agree to cut their crude production to give another boost to prices, a top <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> official predicted. `` It is in their interest to reduce the supply so that we can reach 18 -LRB- dollars a barrel -RRB-,'' <PERSON> Subroto </PERSON>, secretary-general of the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION>, said Monday. The 13 nations that comprise <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> agreed in November to slash production as of Jan. 1 in an effort to raise prices to their target of $ 18 a barrel. The agreement sparked a rally that has lifted the average price of a basket of crudes monitored by <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> to about $ 16 a barrel, up as much as $ 5 from late November. <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> officials want nations outside the cartel to join them in trimming output to spur another price pickup. Representatives of a group of independent countries were meeting Tuesday in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to discuss cuts. They met last month with <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> representatives. `` There is definitely a positive sign that, not only for our interest but for their own interest, they will do something in reducing the supply,'' <PERSON> Subroto </PERSON>, a former <LOCATION> Indonesian </LOCATION> oil minister, said in an interview. `` The more they cut from their production, of course, the sooner we can see it in dollars a barrel,'' he said. He declined to speculate on the level of cuts the non-OPEC nations might put in place. But he said it was likely they would make an offer to <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>, possibly next month. One participant at the non-OPEC meeting said in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> Monday he was `` fairly optimistic about this meeting because we're all very friendly.'' <PERSON> Subroto </PERSON> predicted crude prices would definitely reach $ 18 in the second half of 1989. New <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> figures, he said, show member nations complied in January with the new output accord. The agreedment set an overall ceiling, or quota, of 18.5 million barrels a day for the 13 nations in the first six months of this year. According to <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> figures, 12 countries supplied a total of 17.42 million barrels a day in January, just under the quota of 17.51 million barrels. The cartel said figures from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Emirates </LOCATION> had not yet been received. That nation, however, has persistently overshot its target in the past, according to private analysts. Its current quota is 988,000 barrels a day. <PERSON> Subroto </PERSON> said the supply figures were `` a sign that we are abiding -LRB- by -RRB- our quota.'' Private analysts estimated <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> exceeded its ceiling in January by about a million barrels a day. <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> said, however, it measures the quota by figuring crude production and the amount of oil put into, or taken out of, stock. Production, which it defines as the amount of crude measured at storage facilities, was 18.13 million barrels a day in January for the 12 reporting countries. It was the first time the cartel released monthly production figures. Non-OPEC nations sending representatives to Tuesday's meeting were <LOCATION> Oman </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Yemen </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Canadian </LOCATION> province of <LOCATION> Alberta </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> state of <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> were expected to send observers. <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> members are <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Gabon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Qatar </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Emirates </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>.
