<SECOND>PM-Insurance Tycoon,0917</SECOND>
<HEAD>Absent Tycoon At Center Of Texas Insurance Collapse</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Texas Insurance Woes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVAN RAMSTAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> may have swiped more than $ 20 million from the insurance company he led before it became one of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>' largest industry failures. Or he may be the most prominent insurance industry figure to fall victim to the havoc wreaked on the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> economy by the oil and gas industry collapse. Or both. State and federal investigators trying to understand the failure of <PERSON> Walker </PERSON>'s company, <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mutual </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, may have to wait for his explanations _ first they have to find him. The tycoon, they say, has ignored subpoenas and may have fled the country. The 58-year-old <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> rose and fell in grand <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> style: buying rounds for patrons of his giant honky-tonk, sailing a multimillion-dollar yacht and flying several private planes before being caught in the economic pinch. By the time <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> was taken over by the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> in October 1988, the property-casualty insurer was more than $ 50 million in the red. The size of the failure prompted a crisis of confidence in the state's insurance regulators, who have been accused by some lawmakers of failing to act quickly to help the company's estimated 100,000 customers. `` Mr. <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> is allegedly an example of what can happen when you have this lethargic attitude by a regulatory agency,'' said state Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Montford </PERSON>. <PERSON> Montford </PERSON> serves on the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, which has subpoenaed <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> to appear at a hearing. <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> attorney <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said that based on reliable sources, she believes <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> is in <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> is accused of concealing fraud and funneling premiums from <LOCATION> National </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> to <ORGANIZATION> Walker </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, his Dallas-based holding company that owned the insurance operation, according to a lawsuit filed by <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION>'s state-appointed receiver, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Odiorne </PERSON>. The state has seized some of <PERSON> Walker </PERSON>'s property, including two sterling silver decorative saddles valued at $ 100,000 apiece. <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> owned a home in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> and a ranch in the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Country </LOCATION>. His fortune was spread among more than 60 small companies and real estate properties. Until he transferred his control last year, <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> was part owner of the Million Dollar Cowboy Bar, a <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Wyo. </LOCATION>, honky-tonk with saddles for barstools, silver dollars embedded in the bar and an 11,000-square-foot dance floor. He and two others bought the saloon in 1979. <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> became well-known in the small tourist town during his visits several times a year. Stopping at the Million Dollar, he often would buy a round for the house and occasionally fly friends to <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION>. `` Mostly he just partied,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Hauser </PERSON>, who managed the Million Dollar for eight years. `` He was a nice guy. We seemed to get along real fine.'' <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> could not be reached by The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. Calls to family members were unanswered. Calls to <LOCATION> National </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> were referred to the liquidation office of the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION>. But <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> has said he tried to save the company at the expense of his luxurious lifestyle. `` I never kept money from the company,'' he told the <ORGANIZATION> Dallas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> last fall, adding that he expected to be accused of taking about $ 28 million from <LOCATION> National </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. He said he offered to contribute $ 3 million to the company to help recapitalize it, but the state turned him down. <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> was crippled by the loss of a reinsurance contract with Dallas-based <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>. Republic began providing reinsurance in 1984 for <LOCATION> National </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> under a seven-year contract that anticipated $ 15 million worth of business transferred to the reinsurer each year. In 1985 National County transferred about $ 120 million in premiums to Republic _ eight times the anticipated amount _ and <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> suspended the contract, a spokesman for the reinsurer said. Republic's decision was upheld in court-ordered arbitration, which <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> said rendered <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> unable to maintain its insurance portfolio, primarily automobile coverage to high-risk drivers. Republic, which had honored previous reinsurance contracts with <LOCATION> National </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, refused to enter another. <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> began cutting back. National County took in more than $ 200 million in premiums at its peak, but was down to $ 50 million by the time state regulators took over last fall. As the insurance company's troubles grew, so did those in <PERSON> Walker </PERSON>'s other enterprises, particularly real estate investments for which he'd guaranteed payments before the energy collapse devastated the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> economy. `` I would think that he did what almost every businessman in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> on a big roll did when the tap went dry,'' said <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Ricco </PERSON>, owner of <ORGANIZATION> Diversified </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>. `` He'd just go to other taps that are available.'' <PERSON> Ricco </PERSON> said he and <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> talked only a handful of times in the past five years, but they've known each other for 25 years. `` This lack of integrity I've heard about goes against the grain,'' <PERSON> Ricco </PERSON> said. `` I saw him honor agreements with everyone for years, including me, even to the detriment of himself.'' The <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Postal Inspector's office in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> is leading a criminal investigation of <LOCATION> National </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>'s failure to determine if fraud was involved, inspector <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Horton </PERSON> said. <PERSON