<FIRST>r f PM-Scotus-Workers     02-21 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Workers,0477</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Will Take Up Rail Workers Case from Virginia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today agreed to decide whether a federal law primarily designed to compensate injured longshoremen also applies to railroad employees who work at dockside coal-loading facilities. The court, in cases involving three injured workers in <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, said it will hear arguments by railroads seeking to protect themselves from potentially costly lawsuits. The <ORGANIZATION> Virginia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled last year that the Longshoremen's and Harbor Workers' Compensation Act does not cover the railroad employees. Instead, the state court allowed three injured rail workers to seek potentially greater compensation under the Federal Employers' Liability Act The railroads said the compensation provided by the longshoremen's act should be the exclusive remedy for the three rail employees. The workers are <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwalb </PERSON> and <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> McGlone </PERSON>, who did clean-up jobs for the <LOCATION> Chesapeake </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Ohio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Railway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, and <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Goode </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, a machinist for the <LOCATION> Norfolk </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Railway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. All three worked at coal-loading terminals in the <LOCATION> Hampton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Roads </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, area Ms. <PERSON> Schwalb </PERSON> suffered a serious head injury Jan. 11, 1983, when she fell from a catwalk while going to a nearby area to pick up spilled coal. <PERSON> McGlone </PERSON>'s arm was nearly severed as he was picking up coal from beneath a moving conveyor belt Feb. 1, 1983. <PERSON> Goode </PERSON> suffered a hand injury while repairing loading equipment Feb. 11, 1985. The three sued the railroad company that employed them under the Federal Employers' Liability Act. Lower courts in <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> threw out their lawsuits on grounds that the workers were doing jobs essential to the loading of coal at the terminals, and thus were eligible for compensation only under the longshoremen's act. But the state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> reinstated the suits, deciding the rail employees' jobs were not covered by the longshoremen's act. <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> lawyers supported the railroads' ensuing appeals to the nation's highest court. They said the three workers could get `` potentially lucrative, albeit uncertain, relief'' under the employers' liability law. But government lawyers said in other cases restricting the scope of the longshoremen's act could mean workers in similar jobs would be forced to sue under state laws that provide less compensation for the injured. `` That result would be plainly inconsistent with <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' intent'' in 1972, when it amended the longshoremen's law to expand its coverage, the government lawyers said The <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Railroads </ORGANIZATION> also urged the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> to overrule the <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> court. The association said its members employ some 300,000 workers who, if injured, could sue them for compensation if the <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> court ruling were applied nationwide. The cases are <LOCATION> Chesapeake </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> vs. <PERSON> Schwalb </PERSON>, 87-1979, and <LOCATION> Norfolk </LOCATION> and Western vs. <PERSON> Goode </PERSON>, 88-127.
