<HEAD>Court Rejects Broker's Challenge Of SEC's Anti-Fraud Authority</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today rejected a prominent stock broker's challenge to the power of the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> to crack down on fraud. The court, without comment, left intact rulings that <PERSON> Meyer </PERSON> <PERSON> Blinder </PERSON> and the brokerage firm he founded, <PERSON> Blinder </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Robinson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, say unfairly restrict their business activities. The case stems from a civil <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> enforcement action in 1980 against <PERSON> Blinder </PERSON> and his firm. <PERSON> Blinder </PERSON> began the business in <LOCATION> Westbury </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, and moved its headquarters to <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> in the late 1970s. It became one of the nation's leading underwriters of penny stocks, or low-priced securities. The commission accused <PERSON> Blinder </PERSON> and the firm of deceiving investors in underwriting a $ 25 million sale of stock in <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Leisure </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. The stock sale was intended to finance construction and operation of a casino hotel in <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Matsch </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> ruled in 1982 the firm defrauded investors by withholding important information, including the real risks of the casino venture. The judge said the firm's sales force `` practiced a program of deliberately deceptive misinformation which -LRB- <PERSON> Meyer </PERSON> -RRB- <PERSON> Blinder </PERSON> orchestrated.'' <PERSON> Matsch </PERSON> issued an injunction permanently barring <PERSON> Blinder </PERSON> and his firm from engaging in similar practices. <PERSON> Blinder </PERSON> went back to court in 1986 to have the injunction lifted. He said he and the firm are rehabilitated, noting that he had replaced his sales force since 1982 and had given millions of dollars to charity. He also said the injunction was having dire, unforeseen consequences on his business. He said about a dozen states have taken steps to limit or ban <PERSON> Blinder </PERSON>, <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> from selling securities, and the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> has imposed sanctions based on the court order. <PERSON> Blinder </PERSON> challenged the constitutionality of the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION>'s enforcement powers in such cases. <PERSON> Blinder </PERSON> said it violates the separation of powers to permit the commission to enforce the laws because the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> is only partly accountable to the president. Commission members are appointed by the president, with the consent of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, and may be removed from office by the president for inefficiency, neglect of duty or misconduct. The 10th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> last August refused to lift the injunction against the stock brokerage or its founder. The appeals court rejected arguments that evidence of rehabilitation means the injunction no longer is needed to protect the public. The appeals court also ruled that the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION>'s powers do not violate the Constitution. The case is <PERSON> Blinder </PERSON>, <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> vs. <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION>, 88-850.
