<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>, the tough-as-nails chairman of giant <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, has a master's degree in business administration from <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. So does <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> George </PERSON>, who flies planes for <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, the besieged carrier owned by <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>. The two are on opposite sides of a bitter, escalating conflict that could result in a March 4 strike by the airline's <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> union, which the Eastern pilots and flight attendants have pledged to honor. <PERSON> George </PERSON>, a member of the master executive council of the pilots union at Miami-based <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>, is spreading the union gospel about <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> to Wall Street analysts, creditors of the strapped airline and the public. The campaign is aimed at forcing <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> to sign what <PERSON> George </PERSON> called acceptable contracts with the <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION>, pilots and flight attendants at Eastern. <PERSON> George </PERSON>, 46, does n't pull punches. He's going after his cost-cutting boss with nearly the same fervor he showed flying combat support missions as an <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> captain in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> is `` looking at the abyss. The evil empire is tottering,'' he said in a recent interview in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` We understand the risk -LRB- of striking -RRB-. The worst thing that can happen to us is that we lose our jobs.'' That risk appears r