<HEAD>Most People Believe Takeover Process Is Corrupt, Poll Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A majority of people interviewed in a national survey believe the corporate takeover process in this country is corrupt and should be regulated by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. In the survey released Tuesday, 84 percent of the respondents said they believed mergers and acquisitions take place in a corrupt environment, and two-thirds said the government should place more restrictions on leveraged buyouts. In a leveraged buyout, investors buy a company with largely borrowed funds, and then pay off the loans with the company's cash flow or by selling its assets. The survey, conducted for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> and Lexis, a computerized legal data base operated by the information firm <ORGANIZATION> Mead </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION>, polled 808 people between Jan. 28 and 30. During that time, two congressional committees were holding hearings into possibly restricting LBOs. Public awareness of and concern about LBOs have increased in recent months as a result of <ORGANIZATION> Kohlberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kravis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roberts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s record $ 24.53 buyout of <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. In the survey, which has a margin of error of 3.5 percentage points, 32 percent of the respondents endorsed restructuring tax laws to make it more difficult for LBOs to be accomplished, a step that has received support in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration. Twenty-four percent of the respondents said consumers are hurt the most by takeovers. Fifty-four percent said employees are hurt the most, but one-third also said the gretest benefit of takeover activity was the creation of new jobs. More than one-fifth of the respondents said they or a member of their immediate family had worked for a company that was involved in a takeover in the last three years. Of that group, almost 50 percent reported negative consequences of the takeover, including the loss of a job.
</TEXT>
