<HEAD>Manufacturers Hanover Says Trader Lost $14 Million In Unauthorized
Dealings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hanover </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday a vice president in its government bond trading department lost $ 14 million for the bank last year through unauthorized, secret dealings in Canadian bonds. The bank refused to identify the individual but said the person `` has been relieved of his or her duties.'' The bank said the loss, discovered earlier this month in a routine review, caused it to reduce its reported profit for 1988 by 1.4 percent to $ 952 million, instead of $ 966 million as reported in a January news release. `` The employee is not only very experienced but clever and sophisticated,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Stefans </PERSON>, a bank spokesman. He said the person had been with Manufacturers Hanover about five years and in the business about 20 years. The vice president, without authorization, bought about $ 600 million worth of Canadian federal and provincial bonds over at least a year, mainly in the final weeks of 1988, <PERSON> Stefans </PERSON> said. To conceal the transactions, the person put them in the bank's investment account instead of its trading account, <PERSON> Stefans </PERSON> said Securities held in the investment account are carried on the books at what they cost. When the securities were moved to the trading account, where they belonged, they had to be booked at their lower market value, resulting in the $ 14 million loss, <PERSON> Stefans </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Stefans </PERSON> said the bank had been in contact with the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> state <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. He said it has not yet been determined whether to lodge civil or criminal charges against the executive. The bank has reviewed its procedures for preventing unauthorized trading, <PERSON> Stefans </PERSON> said. But he added, `` A sophisticated enough person, for a particular period of time, if intent on doing something, can probably get away with it.'' `` Everybody on the floor was surprised'' when word of the unauthorized trading got out, said <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Pike </PERSON>, who is in charge of <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bond and municipal bond trading. In addition to the correction in full-year earnings, the bank cut its reported earnings for the fourth quarter by $ 14 million, to $ 210 million from $ 224 million. The earnings did not have to be formally restated because they had never been officially stated, only put out in a press release, <PERSON> Stefans </PERSON> said. Losses from unauthorized trading in recent years have prompted scrutiny of management controls at some Wall Street firms. The giant investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> reorganized its mortgage securities unit after unauthorized trading in a risky form of security caused a $ 275 million pre-tax loss in April 1987.
