<HEAD>Copper Futures Surge On Reports Of Zambian Flooding</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Copper futures prices posted their sharpest gains in three months Tuesday as reports of flood-related mining disruptions in <LOCATION> Zambia </LOCATION> refocused attention on the difficulties faced by many Third World copper producers. On other markets, gold futures rose sharply; cotton futures soared; livestock and meat futures rallied; grains and soybeans were mixed; and energy futures were mostly lower. Copper futures settled 2.9 cents to 8.3 cents higher on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Commodity Exchange with the contract for delivery in March at $ 1.345 a pound, representing a one-day gain of nearly 6.6 percent in the contract's value. The concerns raised by flooding at a <ORGANIZATION> Zambia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Consolidated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Copper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> facility spread well beyond the implications for copper output from <LOCATION> Zambia </LOCATION>, the world's fourth-largest copper producer. The incident served to remind traders of the strain on copper producers in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> as they strive to catch up with the demand created by the strong economies of the industrialized world. Copper production hurdles and labor difficulties have cropped up during the past year in <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> while the major African coppper countries have struggled with transportation problems. Those factors helped push copper futures prices to the record high of $ 1.6475 reached on Dec. 8. But production concerns have faded in recent weeks as copper stockpiles increased. `` A market is very much a forum for changes in sentiment,'' said <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Anagnos </PERSON>, a metals analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Thomson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> McKinnon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGAN