 77.75 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .70 cent to 1.35 cents higher with March at 84.30 cents a pound; live hogs were .35 cent to 1 cent higher with April at 42.82 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .45 cent to the limit 2 cents higher with February at 39.32 cents a pound. Grain and soybean futures finished narrowly mixed on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> after a late surge of buying by commercial interests erased the losses that had held sway for most of the session. Wheat settled unchanged to 2 \ cents higher with March at $ 4.25 a bushel; corn was 2 cents lower to \ cent higher with March at $ 2.69 -RCB- a bushel; oats were -LCB- cent to 7 \ cents higher with March at $ 2.13 a bushel; soybeans were unchanged to 2 cents higher with March at $ 7.46 -LCB- a Energy futures prices finished mostly lower on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> in nervous trading while traders kept one eye on a <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> meeting of oil ministers from non-OPEC countries. West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled .13 cent lower to .03 cent higher with March at $ 18.59 a barrel; heating oil was .27 cent to .98 cent lower with March at 48.92 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .30 cent to .94 cent lower with March at 48.35 cents a gallon.
