<SECOND>AM-PSNH Stock,0538</SECOND>
<HEAD>Magazine Article Apparently Prompts PSNH Stock Price Drop</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL MOKRZYCKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The price of <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hampshire </ORGANIZATION> common stock fell nearly 14 percent Tuesday, apparently because a Barron's magazine article said the stock could become worthless when the utility emerges from bankruptcy protection. The opening of <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> trading in <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> common stock was delayed 31 minutes Tuesday morning because there were too many sell orders and not enough buyers. The stock then lost nearly 20 percent of its value by noon, falling from its Friday closing price of $ 5.50 to $ 4.50 a share. The stock made up a little ground in the afternoon, closing at $ 4.75. <PERSON> Melanie </PERSON> <PERSON> Hale </PERSON>, a utility analyst with <ORGANIZATION> McCarthy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Crisanti </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maffei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said the article in the new issue of <PERSON> Barron </PERSON>'s apparently prompted the fall <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Ashooh </PERSON> said company officials had no other explanation. Headlined `` Common Mistake: A Bankrupt Utility Generates More Speculative Heat Than Light,'' the article was written by <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Fry </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Progressive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and general partner in <ORGANIZATION> Meridian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Strategic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investments </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> L.P. </ORGANIZATION>, two <LOCATION> Indianapolis </LOCATION> firms that invest primarily in companies under bankruptcy protection. Fry noted that <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>'s common stock price has more than doubled in the 13 months since it became the first major investor-owned utility to seek bankruptcy protection since the Great Depression. Debt from its 36 percent share of the stalled <LOCATION> Seabrook </LOCATION> nuclear power project forced <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> to seek bankruptcy refuge. `` In large measure, the rise in the shares reflects investors' faith that <ORGANIZATION> PSNH </ORGANIZATION> _ and its common -LRB- stock -RRB- _ will revive when the company finally emerges from Chapter 11,'' Fry wrote But at least for common stockholders, `` that faith is n't likely to be rewarded,'' Fry wrote. `` Quite the contrary. Holders of the company's common -LRB- stockholders -RRB- could find themselves with totally worthless paper when <ORGANIZATION> PSNH </ORGANIZATION> comes out of Chapter 11'' of the federal bankruptcy code. That is because <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>'s liabilities exceed the market value of its assets, Fry explained, and under bankruptcy law, bondholders and other senior claims must be paid in full before lesser claims may receive any compensation. <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> `` has secured and unsecured obligations of nearly $ 2 billion. It also has nearly $ 500 million of liquidating value of preferred stock, which takes priority in a reorganization. Against the obligations, the company has a conventional utility plant with a book value of about $ 650 million, and its investment in <LOCATION> Seabrook </LOCATION>,'' Fry wrote. He noted that it remains uncertain whether <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON> ever will be allowed to operate commercially, and even if it does, <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> is unlikely to recover what it has invested in the reactor. Even an acquisition offer by <ORGANIZATION> Northeast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utilities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Connecticut </ORGANIZATION>, estimated to be worth $ 2 billion if <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON> operates, would leave nothing for preferred stockholders, much less common stockholders, Fry said. `` It's extremely speculative to think that common shareholders will get anything at all in a reorganization,'' Fry concluded. `` So, if you have an uncontrollable urge to speculate in <ORGANIZATION> PSNH </ORGANIZATION>, its bonds appear to be a much more rational vehicle.''
