<HEAD>Oil Prices Mostly Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Most oil futures prices ended lower in volatile trading Tuesday, reflecting uncertainty over the outcome of a non-OPEC producers conference. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the March contract for <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION>, the benchmark grade of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude, closed 3 cents higher at $ 18.59 after trading as high as $ 18.93 during the session. All other contract months fell. Refined product prices fell sharply. The March contract for heating oil dropped 0.98 cent to settle at 48.92 cents a gallon, after trading at a session high of 50.35 cents. Unleaded gasoline scheduled for March delivery fell 0.94 cent to a closing price of 48.35 cents a gallon. Other contract months also closed down. Crude prices opened higher with buyers caught up in last-day trading on the March contract, analysts said. Prices fluctuated throughout the session on various OPEC-related rumors, they said. Late in the day, a group of producers who do n't belong to the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries, meeting in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, released a statement saying some producers had agreed to either cut or freeze exports during the second quarter of 1989 to help stabilize world prices. However, the group said it would not disclose details of the agreement until next week, which created uncertainty and pressured prices, analysts said. `` It's disappointing because investors were expecting concrete numbers,'' said <PERSON> Nauman </PERSON> <PERSON> Barakat </PERSON>, vice president of energy investments at <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` As long as they do n't know it's difficult to say what the bottom line is ... so the market sold off.'' Analysts have predicted that any cutbacks by non-OPEC nations will be minimal and probably will not alter the current supply-demand balance. Since <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> reduced its production by 3 million barrels daily at the start of the year, prices have risen nearly $ 5 a barrel.
