 Labor Secretary <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> on Tuesday promised to work with labor and piqued the interest of union leaders by calling for a flexible pension system, but she also disagreed with them on several issues. The tone of the first meeting between the <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION> Executive Council and Mrs. <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> was amiable despite the differences, a stark contrast with the first such session of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> presidency, when then-Labor Secretary <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Donovan </PERSON> and the union leaders clashed publicly over the president's economic plans. There was no such acrimony after the meeting with Mrs. <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, although federation President <PERSON> Lane </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirkland </PERSON> said it was inevitable that labor would disagree with the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration on some issues. `` I want continued dialogue with the individuals in that room and certanly I want to leave my door open and be in touch with them,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said after her private meeting with the 35-member council. While Mrs. <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> represented the Republican administration at the meeting, new <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> also was in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> to address the <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION>'s political committee. <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said he briefed the labor leaders on party efforts to gain 500 seats in state legislatures by 1990 and 100 more by 1992, an effort to increase the number of state legislatures, 28, in which Democrats control all chambers. `` Labor's got an extremely important role in the party,'' <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said after the meeting. `` Labor has important political tentacles around the country, it can be very important in electing Democrats.'' At a meeting with reporters, Mrs. <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> raised a proposal to allow workers who change jobs to carry pension funds with them. She said that the administration was studying the issue and that she asked the labor leaders for their input. <PERSON> Kirkland </PERSON> said the federation welcomed her interest and would cooperate. An early disagreement likely will be on congressional proposals to raise the minimum wage. Mrs. <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> would support that if the legislation also carried a sub-minimum training wage for youths; <PERSON> Kirkland </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION> opposes the lower wage. Other areas of apparent disagreement are child care and parental leave, with the administration favoring voluntary policies that might include tax credits. Labor backs Democrat-sponsored bills that mandate some programs. `` We never signed on for a honeymoon,'' <PERSON> Kirkland </PERSON> said when asked to assess labor's early relations with the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration. `` It's early on and we have yet to see what issues or areas we can cooperate on. I'm quite certain there will be some where we disagree.'' The meeting with Mrs. <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> came on the second day of the annual weeklong meeting of the governing body of the 1.9 million-member federation.
