<HEAD>Polaroid Begins Stock Buyback, Including Possible Private Purchases</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Recasts first 3 grafs to CLARIFY that private purchases are
possible, but not certain; SUBS 11th graf pvs, `Shamrock spokesman ...,'
to ADD 2 grafs of Shamrock comment; INSERTS new penultimate graf with lawsuit.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> began a $ 1.1 billion stock buyback Tuesday and said the plan may include $ 325 million in privately negotiated share purchases, a move some analysts said was aimed at the company's hostile suitor. The instant camera maker, which announced Jan. 30 that it would undertake the buyback, began a cash tender offer for 16 million shares at $ 50 a share. In addition, <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> said it would repurchase $ 325 million of its stock on the open market or `` in privately negotiated purchases.'' The offer of private negotiations was seen by some as an invitation to <ORGANIZATION> Shamrock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Holdings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Burbank </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, which holds a 6.7 percent stake in <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> and is pursuing a $ 3.2 billion hostile takeover of the company. `` They're leaving the door wide open for greenmail,'' said <PERSON> Alex </PERSON> <PERSON> Henderson </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` I ca n't think of any other privately held block of stock other than <PERSON> Shamrock </PERSON>'s that would be negotiated individually.'' Greenmail is the practice of buying back shares held by a corporate raider at a premium compared with the market price, in order to thwart a potential or actual hostile bid. Critics say the practice favors raiders at the expense of other stockholders. But some Wall Street analysts said <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> seemed to be making an effort to placate its stockholders by offering a premium for some of their shares. <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION>'s buyback offer of $ 50 a share is $ 5 over <ORGANIZATION> Shamrock </ORGANIZATION>'s last bid and $ 6.25 above Friday's closing price for <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> shares on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> On Tuesday, <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> stock fell 37 -LCB- cents to close at $ 43.37 -LCB- a share. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON>, an analyst for <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Markets </ORGANIZATION>, said the drop reflected anxiety about the possibility of greenmail. `` Polaroid's announcement is good for 30 percent of the stock and bad for 70 percent,'' <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> said. `` It does provide shareholder value for some of the shares, but if they remove <PERSON> Shamrock </PERSON> by doing this, the remaining shares could decline in value.'' <PERSON> Shamrock </PERSON> called the buyback a further attempt at entrenchment by <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION>'s management. `` We believe that <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION>'s partial buyback is a far leass attractive alternative than <PERSON> Shamrock </PERSON>'s $ 45 cash offer for all <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> shares,'' Shamrock President <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gold </PERSON> said in a statement. <PERSON> Shamrock </PERSON>, a television and radio concern owned by the <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Disney </PERSON> family, owns about 4.8 million shares of <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> and is waging a proxy fight for control of the board of directors at the May 9 annual meeting, in addition to its hostile tender offer. <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> has been resisting Shamrock since the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> company made a friendly but unsolicited offer of $ 40 a share last July. In September, <PERSON> Shamrock </PERSON>